t of a quiet grassy valley between low hills to the west and east. The valley continues southwards, while north you can get into open grasslands.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               This is a pleasant grassy area of downlands, stretching on in all directions. Further off to the north and east you can see the edges of a dark, gloomy forest, while some way to the west is a high mountain.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  You are on the north slopes of a green hill. Further up you can see a ruined watch tower on the summit, and below you a pleasant meadow surrounds the hill. Further north you can see a tall mountain.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You are in a lush meadow not far from the lowest slopes of a mountain which towers to your northwest. To the south is a smaller but still substantial hill, and to the east and west the meadow continues.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      You are lost in the magical mist. It billows around you, making strange shapes, and in the distance, muffled by the mist, you seem to hear the sound of unearthly laughter. There seems to be no end to the mist, and no way out....                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            You are on the lower eastern slopes of a tall steep mountain. The surface becomes almost vertical above here, and you will have to climb. You can also get round the slopes of the mountain, to the south or southwest, but northwards they become too steep and treacherous to risk your precious neck on...                                                                                                                                                                                                                   You are clinging frantically to a ledge half way up the almost perpendicular cliff on the eastern side of the mountain. You look down at the dizzying heights below, gulp, and realise you had better move fast. You could edge along the ledge in a northwesterly or southwesterly direction (where the slopes are less steep), or continue up or down the cliff. Above is the top of the mountain.                                                                                                                            You are on the eastern edge of a deep lake at the summit of a tall mountain. In the centre of the lake is a tall black tower, without a visible entrance or windows, seemingly carven out of one vast stone. It juts up at the sky like a blackened finger pointing in malediction. Behind you the mountain drops vertically to form a cliff which only the insane would try to climb; the lake edge continues to the northwest and southwest, though, and you can walk round.                                                  You are on the edge of a deep still lake on the summit of a tall mountain. In the middle of the lake is set a tall dark tower, which casts an aura of gloom over the area; but the view from here is spectacular, and you can see almost the whole of the land, from the forest to the north to the swamps and mudflats at the southern end. The lake edge continues to southwest and southeast, and to the north you could climb down a gentle slope to the edge of a cliff.                                                   You are standing at the very edge of a massive cliff, above a clearing at the foot of the mountain. You have a magnificent view of the forest to the north, which is spread out before you like a map, and turning to the west you can see the moors and, further west, the sea. The eastern view is disappointing, as much of the land in that direction is obscured by mist. To the south the mountain climbs to the summit, to the southeast is a difficult climb, and to the southwest are the western slopes.              You are in green pastures southeast of one wide road and north of another. The southern road leads east towards a hill, while the northwestern one leads beside a wide fast-flowing river northeastwards towards a mountain and a bridge that crosses the river. The two roads converge to the southwest outside the gates of a great city, whose white walls tower above the level of the grasslands.                                                                                                                          You are on the western slope of a green grassy hill. You can go north and south round the hill or west down into pasture lands. Further north you can see a mountain ridge.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     You stand on a long road leading east to west. West are the great stone gates of the city, carven with gargoyles and directly to the north is a deep wide fast-flowing river which passes under the city walls (which also block the way to the southwest). South is a field of tilled earth, and another broad road leads northeast.                                                                                                                                                                                           You're crossing a sturdy wooden bridge which leads east and west across a deep fast-flowing northeast/southwest river. Looking northeast you can see the high mountain from which the river flows, while southwest you can see a high city under whose walls it vanishes. To the west are moorlands; to the east is a stone road. A brass plaque on the bridge's rail reads "SOUTH REALM RECONSTRUCTION 31/10/88. LOOK ON MY WORKS, YE MIGHTY, AND DESPAIR!"                                                                    You are on a well - paved east - west stone road leading through pasture to the north and fields to the south; to the southeast the terrain becomes marshy. Westwards, at the road's end, can be seen a great city walled with stone; north, a mountain rises steeply, and east is a lower hill.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                You are in a deep rocky ravine, cleft between a hill to the west and a higher mountain to the east. Time has made its mark here, etching great gullies and carving elaborate baroque abstracts into the rock. Your footsteps ring about the ravine, and every slightest sound is magnified. North and south you emerge from the ravine - north to a meeting of ways in grasslands close to a forest, south into bleaker moorlands.                                                                                              You are floundering in the northern end of an expanse of salt marsh. There is a strange bitter tang in the air, and the high pitched cries of strange sea birds echo across the water. Southwards is the heart of this evil swamp, and east is firmer ground; to the north are the southern slopes of a hill.                                                                                                                                                                                                                   You are in the heart of the salt marsh, by an evil, black, and stagnant pool, rimmed with scum and slime. There is a foul smell of rot, putrefaction, and decay, and only stinking bogweeds grow in the bitter black soil. From here the marsh spreads like a black stain in all directions.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    You are in the western woods, a shady and secluded spot where only a dim light filters through the trees above. West the forest stops, abruptly, giving way to grasslands; east is a clearing bordered by chestnut trees. North through dense undergrowth can be glimpsed a sheer high cliff shaded by the green forest - your way is blocked in this direction.                                                                                                                                                                You are in a thick marsh stinking of decaying vegetation. East is a boring brown expanse of mudflats, and south is the edge of the sea, lapping lethargically at the sticky shore. North is the heart of the marsh, and it continues to the northwest. To your west is foul mud.                                