 lighthouse (though you can't be sure, because the whole area is veiled with thin mist); southwards you think you can hear the sound of the sea, muffled and faint.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             This is the southern part of a low knoll in a wide expanse of grassland. West is a similar hill; a burnt-out tower stands on its top. South is fen country, bleak and unprepossessing, but the land to the east is worse still, being burnt and broken and strewn with ashes, the remains left by some vast destruction. Further east a tall crag or cliff rears from the ashlands.                                                                                                                                             You are on the east slope of a green hillside. Above, on the summit, is a ruined watchtower. East across a valley is another, lower, hill, and further east you can see a ruined and desolate land.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             You are in a large field of freshly tilled and fertile earth east of the city walls and south of a wide paved road. Fields continue south and east. Further south you can see the sea.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You are in a field, once ploughed and fertile but now covered with rank weeds. Off to the west is another field, followed by the city wall; east the fertile land trails off into salty marshes. Southwards you can see the sea.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                Here the fields from the east trail away, and there is only black and salty soil, where the sea washes listlessly. North are the curtain walls of the city; further southeast the mud continues, and to west, south and southwest is the sea.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   You are in a fertile field, overgrown by weeds, which continues to the north and northeast; to the east the fields trail away into salty marshes. In the northwest corner of the field squats a stricken oak, twisted, malformed and baleful. Behind it is the southeastern corner of the city wall.                                                                                                                                                                                                                            This is is the northern part of the east slope of a low green hill. East is a valley, followed by a similar knoll; you can walk round this hill to north and south.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             You are on the south slope of a green hill. North, above you, is the summit; south are swamplands, and you can walk round the hill to west and east.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            This is plain, fertile pasture land, to the north of a stone road and to the east of a low grassy hill. Further north are the lowest slopes of a mountain. Beyond the road to the south are swamplands.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         This is the southern summit of a low grassy hill. Immediately to your north are the ruins of a watchtower, destroyed by fire; further north you can see a tall mountain, while east is a hill of a similar size to this and beyond that a wasted barren land. Below, to the west, is a wide road leading towards a tall city; steps lead down to it. And looking to the south you can see across the acres of barren swamp to the sea.                                                                                          You are among tall pines, with a carpet of green needles underfoot, patterned by shafts of daylight. Birdsong ripples from high among the branches. East is a beaten track through the forest, and southwest more open woods than these. Southeast through trees you see a clearing, and further a grey mountain looms against the skyline.                                                                                                                                                                                     You are at the summit of this mountain, by a calm lake from which rises a tower of black stone which glisters strangely in the daylight. West, at the foot of the mountain, is a deeply cleft ravine, and further, a green hill crowned with monoliths. North the treetops are laid out like a tapestry, while south a river flows from the lake and cascades down the mountainside to a seashore city in the southwest, preventing you from going round the mountain this way.                                                 You are on the western slopes of a mountain. Above you is a steep climb to the summit, but below and to the west the ground suddenly drops away, forming a deep ravine. Attempting to descend would be extremely foolhardy. The slopes of the mountain continue to northeast and southeast.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     You are at the summit of the mountain, by a still lake. Southwest, and far below, the pleasant landscape is gashed, a deep ravine, beyond which is a green hill topped by standing stones. Northeast, at the foot of the mountain, is a clearing, in the forest that stretches north and northeast. Southwest are wild moorlands, and then a port city, and then the sea, blue - green in its shining waters to the horizon. From the lake centre rises a tower of such blackness that it seems to drink in the daylight.       You are on the mountain's lowest slopes. Southwest you can get down onto moorland, but southeast a river cascades down the mountain slope in a shower of foam and spray, blocking your way completely in this direction. You can continue along the mountainside to the north, though.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You are on the southern slopes of a tall mountain, rising steeply from the flat lands around you. Immediately to your west is an impressive sight; here a river gushes down the mountain slope, roaring and sending gouts of spray upwards as it crashes among the rocks. It is obviously completely impossible to progress round the mountain in this direction, but you could go eastwards, or of course you could head up or down the mountain. A stone paved road is to the southwest.                                      You are at the top of the mountain, by a quiet lake, from which rises a tower, black and absolute. Although the lake is well walled in, nearby to your west a gash has been broken in the wall and through it a torrent of water gushes, away and down the mountainside, preventing your going round the mountain in the direction. You could continue eastwards, though, or go down again.                                                                                                                                     You are at the summit of the mountain, by a calm lake, from which rises a gleaming black stone tower. The lake is walled all around with stone of a similar type, to prevent its escape. You can go round the lake to the west or the east, or return down the mountain.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        You are halfway down the southeast side of a tall mountain which juts steeply from the surrounding landscape. Southwards, at the foot of the mountain itself, a small hill rises from the surrounding grasslands, crowned with some sort of tower.                                                                                                                                              