shadowed by a great mountain which dominates the eastern skyline. To the west can be seen a cliff, and beyond that the sea.                                                                                                     You are wandering on lonely moors to the east of the sea, dotted with heather and gorse. To the east the monotony is relieved by a high hill which rises steeply from the surrounding land.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     You are walking across a wide, bleak moor, which stretches on to north, south and southeast. To the east a hill rises steeply, to the west is a cliff edge and beyond that the sea, while directly south of here is a tall cairn.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               You are standing by a cairn of rough irregular stones on a bleak moor. A chill wind whips across the moor from the west, coming off the Sea which lies not far off in that direction across the scrublands. Off to the southwest you can see what seem to be the walls of a city at the edge of the land, while northeast is a low hill, dwarfed by a mountain behind it. To the southeast you can make out a broad river winding its way across the moor; you might be able to cross it further to the east.                   You are standing in the centre of an area of desolate moorland, where only heather, gorse and clumps of thin grass grow. The moors stretch on in all directions, bounded further to the east and southeast by a broad river which flows from a tall mountain far off east-north-easterly. Closer, to the north, is a low hill with some sort of stone building on top of it, and across the moors to the southwest you can see the walls of a citadel.                                                                          You are at the southernmost extent of the moors, which come to an end here against the walls of a proud city to the southwest and a fast wide river to the south, which flows into the city. The river is much too wide to cross here, though you can see fertile and green lands on the farther bank. The moor continues to the east, and to the west is the edge of a cliff.                                                                                                                                                  You are at the furthest southeastern point of the moors - progress further in this direction is blocked by a fast river coming from the northeast, where it flows from a high mountain. Across the river you can see fertile and green lands in sharp contrast to the bleakness of the moors, but the river is much too wide and deep to cross. The moors continue to north and west; northwest you can see a cairn.                                                                                                            This is the most easterly part of the moors. Here a path runs across the otherwise featureless moorland, leading north through a ravine between a high hill (to the northwest) and an even higher mountain (to the northeast) and east across a bridge which crosses a deep and fast river which flows down the slopes of the mountain. The moors continue to the west and (following the bank of the river) to the southwest.                                                                                                  You are on the southern slopes of a bleak hill rising steeply out of the surrounding moorland. Looking upwards you can see a circle of standing stones on the crest of the hill. To the east the