e ground is steep and dangerous, dropping steeply to a deep ravine before it rises again as a mountain whose size is far greater than that of this hill. You can go to the west, though, where the hill slopes down gently to moorlands before you reach cliffs and the sea, or to the north, where you can see grassy meadows and then a dark forest.                          You are standing on a narrow ledge of slate above a deep ravine on the eastern side of a barren hill. The ledge projects out over the chasm and you can look down at the dizzying drop, and across to the east at the bare grey side of the mountain which rises perpendicularly from the ground below before its slope becomes less steep - hundreds of feet above you - and it climbs upward to a flat top. The only exit from here is a scramble up the eastern slope of the hill - tiny in comparison - to its own summit.  You are at the summit of this bleak hill, an evil-looking place obviously used for some dark ritual in the Realm's distant past. Around you loom great grey monoliths, encircling and enclosing you, and at the centre of the circle there is a flat black stone, worn smooth, polished, and tainted with many rust-brown stains. You can descend to the west and south towards the barren moors, to the north to meadows and wooded land, or to the east - a dangerous climb down to a ledge above a deep ravine.              You are just below the summit of a barren hill. Above is a circle of standing stones, while below are purple moors and then the Western Sea.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    You are below the summit of the hill, and can now see clearly the circle of grey stones which surmounts it. To the east the ground falls away steeply to make a deep ravine between this hill and a mountain further east. To the south are dreary moors, and beyond them to the southwest a white-walled citadel on the edge of the Sea.                                                                                                                                                                                       You are walking a precarious path along the edge of steep cliffs. Below, the sea crashes against jagged rocks, and looking further out, you can see the vast expanses of boundless ocean stretching out to the misty horizon. The cliffs and the path continue to north and south, and northwest an extremely unsafe path leads down the edge of the cliff. To the east another path leads off into grasslands.                                                                                                                 You are on a grassy cliff path, leading north and south. To the west are dangerous cliffs, and looking down you can see a sheltered cove - indeed an almost inaccessible cove, as no-one would dare the jagged rocks connecting it to the beach further north. To the east is moorland, and further east a bleak hill.                                                                                                                                                                                                          Here the cliff path comes to an abrupt end: south are high city walls. East are moors, in which a cairn of grey stones has been raised.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         You are walking gingerly along a narrow ledge hewn into the cliff to your east. It slopes down to a sandy beach below, and up to the edge of the cliff. Thousands of seabirds are all around you, screaming their hoarse cries over the roar of the sea.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        You are in a large room with carven stone walls and ceiling, lit by a gentle glow which seems to be all around without a definite source. To the east an ornate and rune - enscribed door is set in a stone archway. In the floor strange and occult symbols surround a large pentacle. All around you can hear the sound of running water.                                                                                                                                                                                     You are standing in the centre of a dark and gloomy cave, dimly illuminated by the light from an iron gate to the north. The air is dank, cold and very still, but listening intently you seem to detect a dull booming sound, distant and faint. A tunnel hewn from the rock slopes downward and to the south, into the darkness.                                                                                                                                                                                              You have been thrown into the Wizard's Dungeon, an area designed to hold malefactors and those who disturb the peace of the Realm (though it is misused occasionally...) Looking gloomily about you realise that there is little chance of escape : the only exit is a shaft set in the ceiling, 30 feet above, through which a dim light filters. A notice reads "DON'T QUIT!"                                                                                                                                                 