                                                You are in deep snow on a cliff ledge. West is a niche in the cliff face, but you cannot continue further east, nor can you ascend, nor can you descend without breaking your neck. You have a fine view from here; first a snowy plateau, then a steep hill of ice. Further north a chasm, and still further, at the far end as the cliffs close in, a dark castle guarding the pass, and east and west the black harsh cliffs closing in to the northern end.                                                                 You are in a hollow in the cliff face - deep, but no protection from the wind, which still catches you full in the face. North is a chilly - looking waste, glittering with ice and frost, with a harsh yet not altogether ugly appearance, quite delicate, even. Above you is a scramble up the north cliff face, jagged, possibly, painful, and more than a little dangerous, to a niche set deep in the rock.                                                                                                                Here the cliff rock, though hard, has given way, and hundreds of tiny black pebbles and needle - like splinters of rock are half embedded in the snow, and here and there, some hard black rocks and boulders, some of a considerable size. West and south are snowy plains, and southwest is an area of ice and cold winds. Passage east is blocked by the dark (if somewhat crumbling) cliffs, and northwest is the corner of an icy hill, too steep to climb.                                                                Here, you are almost hemmed in on every side, south and west and southwest by the harsh black cliffs that provide so much of the scenery here in the North, east by a lower cliff, more jagged - you realize that that must be the west side of Stilton Gorge, and north by an icy hill, almost vertical and much too steep to climb. There is only a gap northeast by which you could exit, and this gives you a view only on snowfields until the invariable black cliffs.                                                    This is a gully between cliffs to north and south and east. From the east, and lower cliff a waterfall has flowed, but now it is still and solid, frozen into ice by the cold of this land. In it glitter many strange or valuable objects - some half hidden and merely a glitter of gold, others more visible; a crown, a chairleg, and a great deal of household rubbish - all trapped in the ice and out of your reach.                                                                                                     You are on the highest point of an icy hill. West is the sheer cliff face, and north and south the ice slope is too steep to descend safely, so if you wish to leave you must make your way down eastward to the lower slopes of the hill. From here you can see to the north a chasm, and beyond that a dark castle guarding the North Pass.                                                                                                                                                                                   This is a niche between an icy hillside to the south and curving to the east, and the blank black face of the cliff to the west. South you could perhaps climb the hill, but there seems to be more scope to the north. Although north and northwest after a while you would come to the brink of the chasm, the cliff which now blocks your way to the west falls away there, while northeast there seems to be a way to skirt the chasm altogether.                                                                           You are on the northern slope of an icy hill, the summit being to your west. The wind blowing here is exceptionally sharp and cold, coming as it does from the north. North also you can see snowfields, to which you could descend, a deep chasm, and still further north a black castle guarding the Northern Pass, before which lie the snowy Coldlands. South you can travel