e occupant must be around somewhere - and bad luck is what you don't need right now, some eighty feet or more above the ground...                                                               You have come to the very top of the chestnut tree, and, clinging precariously to the slender branches, a view of the Realm spread out below you. To the west and east you can see the forest, extending around you on every side; further west is the sea, and further east the ruins of an abbey. Northwards you can see the top of the high cliff that blocks travel in that direction, a narrow catwalk before it plunges downwards again to a cold and snow-covered land.                                                  You are passing under the great gatehouse of the city. Westwards you can see along a dusty cobbled road to an open square; eastwards are the tall city gates, sturdy oak studded with brass and reinforced by metal bars. To your south is a small alcove, set in the gatehouse's mighty stone walls.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           You are walking briskly along a wide cobbled east-west street running between tall buildings, locked and barred to prevent your entry and seemingly deserted. To the east the street leads out of the city towards a strong gatehouse, while to the west it continues towards the town square. Southwards a narrow alley leads between buildings.                                                                                                                                                                               You are walking along a broad cobbled street between tall forbidding buildings, east of the town square. The town is deserted and the silence is deathly; you tread carefully for fear of disturbing some spectre of long ago. Eastwards the road leads towards the exit of this uncanny city.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  You are in a small alcove. North of here is a low door which would allow you to leave, or you could ascend a flight of steps; above you you can see daylight.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   You are near the top of the flight of spiral steps which allowed the guards, in the days of the city's glory, to gain access to the gatehouse top from the guard alcove below. But these stairs cannot have fulfilled their original purpose for many a year now, and dust lies thick on the stone treads. Above you is daylight.                                                                                                                                                                                               You have come to the top of the great gatehouse, main bastion of the city defences in the days when its lords were supreme rulers of the Realm. You can look through the arrow slits, see the holes where boiling oil would be poured, lean over the high battlements where - if all else failed - the defenders would grapple hand-to-hand with their opponents. But all is deserted, and looking over the western wall you can see the signs of decay in the great city. You can go down, or north or south along the walls.  You are on the section of the northern city wall closest to the gatehouse; from the narrow walkway that used to allow the guards to patrol the walls, you can look eastwards over the road that leads into the remainder of the Realm. Westwards, leaning over the battlements, you can see houses, and nearer the wall, a tavern. You can continue along the wall to the north.                                                                                                                                                You are on a narrow walkway on top of the city walls, running north-south. From here you have a good view - looking west - of the northern section of the city, while eastwards you can see across the southern part of the Realm. The walkway continues in both directions; further south it leads onto the gatehouse.                                                                                                                                                                                                         You are on a walkway on the top of the northern city walls, above the West River which flows under the wall and into the city here. Here, too, the city wall bends sharply westwards, so that to leave this part of the wall you can go either south or west.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   You are on an east-west walkway along the top of the northernmost end of the city wall. Northwards, looking over the battlements, you have a view down to bleak moorland, and northwest cliffs, while in sharp contrast to the south are the palace grounds and the spires, domes and minarets of the palace itself, once the centre of the Realm.                                                                                                                                                                              This is a dead end, since a building has collapsed across the street to the south. You may return northwards. Alternatively there's a small nondescript building to the west whose entrance is a shimmering wall of light - clearly some sort of magical portal - which you could try to pass through.                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You are at the northwestern corner of the city walls; the walkway leading to this location goes south and east from here. Looking westward over the battlements you can see the sea washing against the cliffs below; the western wall is on the very edge of the Realm.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        You are on a north-south walkway leading along the western part of the city walls. Below and to the west is the sea; to the east is the western part of the palace. Southwards along the walkway the wall ends in a round tower.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                You are at the top of the northern tower, built to defend the city from attack by sea. It overlooks the harbour - to the south - and the sea washes against its lower western and southern walls. It is joined to the north by a walkway which leads along the length of the main city wall, designed to allow guards to patrol it. The only other exit is down a ladder to the lower level.                                                                                                                                    You are in the lower chamber of the north tower, which in bygone days defended the city harbour from attack. Now, however, it is cold, damp, and decidedly chilly; a cold wind blows from the sea to the west and whistles through the arrowslits. A door leads east, but it is jammed and cannot be opened; perhaps something is blocking it from the other side. The only exit, therefore, is a ladder which leads up onto the top of the tower.                                                                              You are on a north-south walkway leading along the top of the part of the southern city walls nearest to the gatehouse to the north. Eastwards, leaning over the battlements, you can see fields and - further - a marsh. West you look across the roofs of a maze of small houses and twisting backstreets.                                                                                                                                                                                                                    You are walking along the top of the city walls. The walkway between the battlements continues to north and south; further north you can see the main gatehouse.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                You are on a part of the southern city wall which curves west in one direction and north in another. Looking southeast you can see over fields and mudflats to the sea, while northwest over the battlements you can see the roof of an intriguing granite building, seemingly without doors or windows, which has escaped the destruction vented on much of the rest of the city around it.                                                                                                                                    You are walking along an east-west walkway on top of the southern city wall. Southwards you can look over fields towards the sea, while northwards you can observe the desolation wrought on the once proud city. Buildings lie in ruins all around this area - the roads are blocked by fallen masonry, and here and there are great pits and chasms in the earth. Some terrible catastrophe must have overtaken the inhabitants to wreak such destruction.                                                                    You are at a sharp corner in the city wall where it bends north and east; walkways lead along it in both these directions. From here you can look across the great western ocean to the west and southwest; but looking southwest an ominous sight catches your eye. A mountain, remote but clear, rises from the sea in this direction; and from its peak trails a faint plume of smoke. Here, surely is the agency that has wrought the destruction in the city below. An active volcano!                                     You are on a north-south walkway, leading along the top of the high city wall. North of here the walkway leads onto the top of a round tower, while south it bends east; west you can look over the sea as it washes against the base of the wall, and east you look down over the battlements onto a street and some relatively undamaged buildings.                                                                                                                                                                           You are on the top of a large round tower which in former days would have guarded the harbour from attack, together with the North tower on the other side of the harbour. It is based partly in the sea, which washes round its lower walls to the north and west; to the south a walkway leads onto the city wall, and a ladder allows you to descend to the lower level.                                                                                                                                                     You are in the lower part of the south tower, built to guard the harbour from attack. Since the destruction of most of the city it has been disused, and it too suffered in the eruption of the volcano; part of the upper western wall has been destroyed and cold wind and spray from the sea blow in through the gaping hole. A door leads out of the tower to the southeast, and a ladder allows you access onto the roof of the building.                                                                                  You are in the city square, dominated by a statue of some forgotten hero on a high plinth. The square is strewn with chunks of rubble from the destruction of the city; but it is still a quiet and a pleasant place, the silence only broken by the sound of birdsong and by the murmur of the distant sea. Roads lead from the square to the north, south, east and west; in all other directions the way is blocked by tall buildings.                                                                                       You are on a north-south cobbled road south of the city square. Further south it joins other streets to form a crossroads. East are tall buildings, locked and boarded up since their inhabitants fled the city; west are the ruins of a building destroyed in the city's fall.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 You are in a small cobbled square where four roads meet to form a crossroads. In the middle of the square a fountain used to play; but now it is choked with dust and part of the basin has been broken away. Rubble litters the ground from the ruins of a large building to the northwest; but in most other directions the buildings are unscathed. Boarded-up houses are to the northeast, to the southwest is a shop of some kind, and to the southeast is a large granite building, seemingly without an entrance.        This is a short north-south road ending abruptly at the edge of a deep chasm in the earth to the south, too wide to jump. To the east and west are the walls of large buildings, blocking movement in those directions; so you must return north.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               This road leads into the winding backstreets of the City to the east, or west to a crossroads. To the south it passes a large and imposing granite building, whose purpose is unguessable; its windows are high and narrow, and the single door in its walls is impossible to open.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             This narrow alley leads between tall gloomy buildings, south into the maze of the backstreets or north onto the main city road.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 This road, so named because of the many warehouses (now mostly ruined) which used to stand on its southern side, runs east to a crossroads and west to a three-way junction. Northwards is rubble from the destruction of some large building, which you can cross.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             This is where Tower Street, running north-south, is joined by Warehouse Road to the east. Tower Street runs parallel to the western city walls, and further north you can see the tower that gives it its name.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 This is the northern end of Tower Street; it ends at the door of a tall round tower, part of the city defences. East and northeast are the ruins of a large building, west are the city walls, south is the junction of Tower Street and Warehouse Road and north and northwest is the South Tower itself.                                                                                                                                                                                                                      This east-west road is - or used to be - the main street of the city. Along here would roll the wagons laden with goods from the many ships that anchored in the city port; along this street would walk the warriors, adventurers and magicians who had bought their passage to the Realm to seek adventure. Now it - and the rest of the city - are deserted and silent.                                                                                                                                                      This wide north-south street, running between elegant houses to west and east, joins the city square to the south and crosses a river to the north. Eastwards a narrower road leads off the main street.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        You are standing amid rubble and broken masonry in the centre of a large expanse of ruins. Perhaps once some great mansion or temple, this building must have suffered a direct hit from the lava of the erupting volcano; only a couple of marble columns remain, pointing forlornly at the sky. To the northwest is the edge of the city harbour; in all other directions (except northeast, where the way is blocked by buildings still standing) you can get onto one of the city's roads.                                  Here you would once have come, if you had lived in this city while it still throve and grew, to buy almost anything that you could have needed. Everything from basic foodstuffs to the most esoteric magical ingredients could have been found here. Unfortunately, when the city fell, this made it a perfect target for looters and robbers, and so very little of any use remains on the broad mahogany shelves or the wide marble counter. The only exit is through a doorway to the northeast.                            This is the west end of Harbour Street, where it meets Chandler's Street running north and south along the edge of the harbour. Steps lead down from here into the murky water.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 You are crossing the river which flows through the city, going over a mighty stone bridge made in the days when the city was powerful. It arches up high above the water, carven with gargoyles and curious stone faces which stare and leer from the rock. North and south is normal road again; further north you can see the domes and high towers of a palace.                                                                                                                                                              This narrow east-west street runs between various small shops, most locked and closed to keep out intruders. Silver Alley was so named because of the trading - buying and selling, haggling and bartering - that went on here once. But there is little sign of that now. West Silver Alley joins Palace Street, and east it continues.                                                                                                                                                                                        This is the north end of Chandler's street, bounded by the city river to the north and the edge of the harbour to the west. East you might be able to get into a derelict warehouse, and south Chandler's street forms a junction with Harbour Street.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          These are the steps which lead down to the dirty water of the harbour and up to the street running along the harbour's edge. They were built to allow people with boats to come and go between the greater ships that were once moored in this harbour - and without a boat you will not be able to go any further in this direction.                                                                                                                                                                                           You have come to the southern end of Chandler's Street, and the southern end of the quayside. There is very little here of interest, apart from the sea to the west and the rest of the street to the north; in all other directions are ruins, though across them to the southwest you can see a round tower.                                                                                                                                                                                                                  You have come to the northernmost end of Palace Street, and have reached a high fence of metal railings which cuts off the palace grounds from the rest of the city. Two wrought-iron gates stand to the north, but although they were once firmly padlocked and formed a barrier they are broken down and do so no longer; you can pass through them on to a tree-lined avenue leading up to the palace.                                                                                                                       You are on an east-west road, between two largish shops that seem to have been left unlocked and have not been damaged by the catastrophe that devastated so much of the rest of the city. To your north is an armourers, to your south a shop whose sign reads "Curios and Antiques." To the east Silver Alley comes to an end, and to the west it joins Palace Street.                                                                                                                                                        This derelict warehouse once housed many of the exotic treasures that were brought back by ships from distant countries. Since the fall of the city, though, it has been looted many times and partially burnt, so that little of any great value remains. You might find something if you look, though...                                                                                                                                                                                                                      This is the end of Silver Alley; you cannot go any further east, because of the city walls, and the shop to the south is boarded up and inaccessible. To the north, however, stands a disreputable-looking tavern, whose sign realistically shows an orc swinging his morningstar towards the viewer. Above the open door is written the name of the inn "The Ball and Chain". If you don't like the look of this you can head westwards down the road.                                                                         The Armourer's shop was one of the most important in the city in the time when it was a meeting-point for adventurers and heroes. The brackets you see on the stone walls would have held a wide range of swords, axes, maces and polearms for those who wanted to face the Realm's many dangers. Obviously since the city's fall these weapons have been much in demand and have been scattered about the land, but you might find that one or two have been left behind. You can leave the shop to the south.                 You have entered a fairly large shop which once sold antiques and curios in the days when there was a buying market for such things. However this shop, like most of the buildings left open in the city when its inhabitants fled, has been looted and as a result most of what is left in here is mere worthless junk. The only exit is to the north.                                                                                                                                                                         This is the "Ball and Chain" tavern, once frequented, in happier days, by all the warriors, thieves, mercenaries and adventurers of the cityport. It seems to have escaped the fall of the city and the chaos that followed reasonably structurally intact, as far as you can tell. You can lean on the bar and chat here - assuming there's anyone to chat to - and there's even a tap here from which you could fill yourself a glass of beer. The only exit is the street door to the south.                                 This is a room where the Coders, Gods, Demigods and so on store the objects that may be useful at some point in the game but are not at the moment. It is designed as a sort of adjunct to the Wizard's Room to keep its burden down. Mortals are DEFINITELY not allowed in here.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               You have come to a relatively clear part of the backstreets and are standing in a small square in the corner between the eastern and southern city walls. Nestling against the southern wall is a small shop, whose sign reads "Irata and co. Suppliers of quality gems." The door is open and you may enter; or you may go back into the maze.                                                                                                                                                                                 You are on the outskirts of the maze of backstreets and there is a way to leave it altogether by following a dark alley northwards between two large buildings. Or you can go into the backstreets to south, west and east.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     You are on the western edge of a maze of twisting turning backstreets. A road to the west offers some escape or you can go deeper in to the east.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               You are wandering in a maze of twisting turning back streets, all alike, which seem to go on for ever.                                                          