e of twisting back streets which seem to go on for ever. You are disorientated and cannot find any familiar landmarks, nor can you be certain as to the direction from which you came.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You are hopelessly lost in a maze of sidestreets and back alleys, which twist and turn as far as you can see. Your sense of direction is confused and you cannot be sure of finding your way out.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               You are wandering in a maze of twisting turning back streets, all alike, which seem to go on for ever.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You are wandering in a maze of twisting turning back streets, all alike, which seem to go on for ever.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You are wandering in a maze of twisting turning back streets, all alike, which seem to go on for ever.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You are in a maze of twisting back streets which seem to go on for ever. You are disorientated and cannot find any familiar landmarks, nor can you be certain as to the direction from which you came.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You have entered a small and poky shop. For some reason this shop was not raided when the city fell - perhaps because the raiders couldn't find their way here - and so most of the contents are intact, though some are in disarray, as though the owner left in a hurry. Unfortunately most of the metal cases on the walls are securely locked and bolted, so you can't get at their contents...                                                                                                                             This is the northern end of the beach, bounded to the north and east by high cliffs and to the west by the sea. Looking far out in this direction you think you can see a small island. The beach continues to the south.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       You are scrambling about on the north edge of some black rocks, wet and slippery with sea spray. North is a sandy beach and west is the sea. South the rocks continue.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You are climbing over sharp and spiky black rocks, slippery with seaweed and water, west of a tall white cliff. Above your head gulls wheel and scream, darting down to the sea to the west to catch fish. Further north the rocks end.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         You are scrambling over wet and weedy rocks west of a tall cliff. West you can see an interesting rockpool; further south the rocks slope down to a small beach.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                You are at the southern end of a group of slippery black rocks. Further south is a small sheltered sandy cove, and west is the sea, crashing against the rocks.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 This sandy cove, sheltered on both sides by cliffs, is a strangely quiet and peaceful place. The sea, which crashes against the black rocks to the north, rolls in quietly to the west; even the screaming of the gulls seems distant and faint. To the east is a tall cliff, grassed on the top, and with a small passage in it - naturally carved by the sea - which you might be able to crawl down.                                                                                                                         You are crawling down a narrow east-west tunnel, lit dimly from the west. Further east it seems to broaden out, but it is too dark to see clearly.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              You have entered a rounded natural cave, tall enough to stand up in and with a smooth sandy floor. It is entered by a narrow crawlway from the west and has no other exit. In your flickering light you can see that this would be an ideal place for someone to hide treasure; but maybe somebody else has thought of this first.                                                                                                                                                                                              You are on the southern side of a large area of black rock, being splashed by the sea as it batters against the edges of the rock to the south. Further north you can see a large rockpool; east are cliffs, and northwest the rocks continue.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  You are by a large and interesting rockpool, filled with curious weeds and fishes; through the clear water you can see crabs scuttle across the stony bottom. Anemones fringe the edges of the pool, waving their tentacles at the tiny crustaceans swimming through the water. West and east, north and south, the rocks continue; further west is the sea and further east cliffs.                                                                                                                                            You are on black rocks, close to the sea to the north and an interesting rockpool to the south. The rocks continue to the west and the east; to the east is a tall cliff while westwards the rocks eventually give way to sea.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  You are scrambling over a particularly slippery and treacherous area of black rocks, part of a larger area which juts out into the sea to the west. The sea blocks travel to the north, unless you have a boat, but the rocks continue in most other directions.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                This is the southern edge of a large area of black rock, jutting out from the main coastline of the land to the east into the sea to the west. The sea splashes against the rocks to the south, making it impossible to continue that way on foot (and even if you do have a boat, it might not be a good idea to put out to sea so close to the rocks) but in other directions the rocks continue.                                                                                                                             You have reached the northwestern edge of the black rocks, and without a boat you cannot get any further to north or west, but must return eastwards the way you came. But this is a good place to look across the sea, to see - you think - tiny islands set in the gleaming water of the vast ocean, and to wonder what strange things might lurk in the emptiness of the sea.                                                                                                                                                Here is the southwestern edge of the black rocks, and you can go no further to south or west without a boat - and even if you did have a boat, it might not be advisable to put out to sea so close to these dangerous rocks. But you can look out from here across the sea, see the tiny islands set like jewels in the bright ocean; and far to the south-south-west you can see a mountain, remote yet clear and somehow menacing, from whose peak a faint pall of smoke rises.                                              This is the eastern end of the harbour of the city, and a small flight of stone steps lead upwards to dry land further to the east. From your boat you can see the high buildings and stone towers of the great city, almost as if it was still inhabited; and you can imagine the days when this port was the gateway to the realm, and tall, stately ships or slave-rowed galleys would come here from far away bringing cargoes of treasure.                                                                                 This is the mouth of the city harbour; further west is the open sea, while eastwards it is possible to get onto dry land. North and south you are flanked by high stone round towers, built to defend the city from attack from the sea in the days of its glory; looking east you can see the ruins and desolation that overtook the city, leaving little of the southern part standing; and far off to the southwest you can see the agent of that destruction, a remote mountain with a little smoke coming from its peak.   You are close to the southern side of a group of tall and jagged rocks which block progress further north - nobody in their right mind would risk certain death by rowing any closer. The sea continues to west and south, and east you can get in to dry land and safety.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      This is the northern part of a small desert island, and here is the only visible sign that mankind has ever taken any interest in this dry and inhospitable place. A tall tower stands close by, made from some strange black stone and apparently without either doors or windows - its purpose is unclear, except that it might of course contain something of value - if you could get inside. Apart from that, the sea is to the north and a group of palms to the south, and you could always walk round the island W or E.This is the east side of a small island, and to the east the sea washes gently up the sandy beach. West of here you can see a small group of palms, and further north round the island's coast there is a tall black tower without any visible entrance. You can also walk round the island to the south.                                                                                                                                                                                                                       You are struggling to keep your small boat from being dashed against vicious black rocks to your east and south. It is obviously impossible to try to land here, though you could possibly row round the rocks to north and south and in that way get to dry land. Or you could head out to sea, to the west.                                                                                                                                                                                                                   You are close to the southwest side of a group of vicious black rocks at the base of a tall white cliff to the east. You have to row with all your might to keep from being caught up and dashed against the rocks by the waves; and it is obviously impossible to land here, though you could head round the rocks to the north or south, or of course head west out to sea.                                                                                                                                                   You have reached the safety of a relatively calm and safe area of water, just to the west of a pleasant-looking sandy cove where you could land without danger. The cove is flanked with cliffs on all sides except where it is open to the sea; in the cliff wall directly to your east you think you can make out a small tunnel, perhaps the entrance to a cave, which might be worth investigating. North of here are dangerous rocks, but south and west the sea appears reasonably safe.                                  This is the south beach of a desert island, sandy and inhospitable except for a cluster of palms in its centre (directly to the north) which afford some protection from the sun's heat. You can head into the sea to the south (if you have a boat) or you can go round the island to the west or east. To the west you notice a tall cone of rock, rising suddenly and incongruously from the sand.                                                                                                                           This is the western side of a small desert island, whose only vegetation is a group of palms to your east. The main feature of this section of the island is a strange cone of stone, rising suddenly from the sand and towering to a peak, to your southwest; this feature of the landscape - possibly formed long ago in an eruption of the great volcano to the south? - blocks your access to the sea from this area of the island. It can be climbed via some steps; or you can go round the island to north or south.     You have managed to enter the black tower; but its interior is not very interesting. Whoever designed it must not have meant it to be viewed from inside; the walls are bare, the floor only sand, and there are no stairs to the top, just a view up to the blue sky. The only thing to catch your attention is a tall pedestal, made from the same black stone as the tower itself, and clearly designed to hold something of value.                                                                                          You are on grey and uninteresting sea, south of mudflats where you could land if you chose. To the east is a strange mist and far off west-south-westerly you can see the peak of a volcano rising from the sea.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                This is grey, listless and boring sea south of acres of mudflats - the best approximation you're likely to get to "dry" land round here. You are also close to the western side of some very peculiar mist, coming down thickly like a curtain to your east. You feel a peculiar dread of rowing into it, and though you realise this is probably magical, you cannot resist it.                                                                                                                                                You are rowing through fairly calm sea close to a sandy beach to your east. In all other directions the sea continues.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You are in the sea, close to the western coast of the Realm. Looking east you can see a sandy beach, and further a cliff with a narrow path winding up it. In all other directions the sea continues, though to the southeast are some black and dangerous-looking rocks.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       You are on the open sea, some distance from any land, though to the southeast are dangerous and jagged rocks, and to the northwest and - much further off - to the southwest, you can see islands rising from the water.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        You're on the sea, fairly close to some nasty black rocks to the east, but otherwise far from any land.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         Your boat is floating gently on calm water some distance from land, though you can see cliffs to your east and to the southwest there rises an island, steep and crowned with some kind of building. You think you can make out another island to the northwest and another much further south.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 You are rowing quite close to a tall white cliff - to your east - which blocks movement in that direction. Looking up you can see the grass on the edge of the cliff, and for a moment wish you were back safe on dry land. This could be achieved by rowing north - where there is a small cove where you could easily land - or south, where you could get into the harbour of the great city. Or you could head west and out to sea again.                                                                                   This part of the sea is just outside the western mouth of the harbour of the great city, and looking east you can see the great stone towers which guarded the harbour in days of yore, and further east the tall buildings - now shabby and decaying - which were once the houses of rich merchants and princes. Looking westwards you think you can see a tall island, coming to a point on which is set some kind of building; and far off to the southeast you can make out another island.                                 You are southwest of the coast of the Realm, where the land slopes down to meet the water; you can land here, or continue round the coast to the southeast, or head out to sea in any other direction.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You are on a part of the southwestern sea which makes you feel strangely dull and apathetic. The waves move sluggishly and hypnotically, faint shreds of mist swirl around you although there seems to be no wind to speak of; even the gulls seem distant and faint. You feel sleepy and realise that you had better muster your strength and get out of here....                                                                                                                                                              Mist is all around you and you cannot see more than a few yards in any direction. The mist muffles all sound and makes it difficult to judge direction; it makes you a little claustrophobic and more than a little apprehensive as you wonder if you will ever manage to get out of the mist....                                                                                                                                                                                                                               The mist here almost completely obscures your view; it is difficult to see your oars in the water, only a few feet away, let alone find your way to land. You are disorientated and you feel that if you push on into the mist, you are unlikely to find your way out again....                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 You are close to the south side of some dangerous rocks which are clearly not navigable even in your small boat; that way is blocked, though you can go in any other direction across the sea. To the southwest you can see an island, and some way to the east is the mainland.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                Not far to your west you can see a fairly barren and sandy island, which is nonetheless safer than the waters of the open sea in all other directions. The mainland is now some distance to the east.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           You are on the open sea. Some distance to the west you can see an island, bare and inhospitable but better than the ocean; to the east is the mainland, not very far away.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      You are quite close to the small island to your west, and you can see that the building surmounting its peak is built in the shape of a skull! Some evil temple, perhaps, or a castle of some grim lord? One thing is sure; the building looks deserted, and looks, too, as though it has been so for some time. You could head west towards the shore of the island, or east towards the mouth of the city harbour, not far away; or you could continue across the open sea to the north or the south.                         You are not far off the southeastern shores of a barren island, little more than a cone of rock rising out of the water but surmounted by an evil-looking building, carved in the shape of a skull facing eastwards. If you don't fancy investigating it more closely, you could head east towards the shore or southwest towards a larger island - a volcano.                                                                                                                                                                  This part of the sea is close to land in three directions; northeast is the mainland, northwest Skull Island (so called because of the building, carved like a skull, surmounting it) and southwest a second island, this one, you realise with some trepidation, an active volcano. If none of these choices satisfy you you can continue through the open sea in any other direction.                                                                                                                                         This is the far south of the sea, and quite some way now from any land, excepting the great volcanic island not far off to the west. To the south the ocean seems to stretch on for ever to the east is a thick bank of mysterious mist.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        You are comprehensively lost in a bank of incredibly thick fog, so dense that you can hardly see the end of the boat. You have lost all sense of direction and realise the best thing to do would be to get out of this - quickly....                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           You are rowing into the blue emptiness of the northern sea, devoid of land. To your south you can see the coast of a small sandy island, not far away but gradually receding.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   You are in the sea, off the northeastern side of a small desert island; not far up the beach to your south you can see a strange black tower which might be worth investigating. You can row round the island to the west or southeast, or head out to sea in any other direction.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              You are some way northwest of the beaches at the edge of a small desert island, and can see quite clearly from here its main features; a strange tower made of some black stone which rises from the sand in the northern part of the island, a cluster of palms in its centre and further south a large outcropping of rock. West and north of you here is the open sea, with no islands in it as far as your vision reaches; south and east you can sail round the edges of the island.                                       You have rowed quite close to the western side of a small desert island, but cannot land by going east as a tall outcropping of rock blocks off all the western and southwestern side of the island from the sea. You could get onto the north beaches of the island by going northeast, though, or you could go north or south round the island or west into the open sea.                                                                                                                                                     You are in calm waters, close to the southwestern side of a small island; access to its shores is blocked off by a large rock formation which encircles the whole of the island's western and southwestern edge. You can row round the island to the east or the north, or head out into the western ocean or southwards towards another island not far away.                                                                                                                                                                   You're a little way south of a gently sloping sandy beach, the southern part of a small desert island. Looking north you can see a cluster of palms in the island's centre, and looming over them a dark tower, built of gleaming black stone; while to the northwest is a natural outcropping of stone which blocks the way to the western parts of the island from the sea.                                                                                                                                                   Northwest of here you can get onto the southern beaches of a small desert island. In all other directions is sea; you can see no end to it to the west, though to the east you can make out white cliffs.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       West of you are the eastern beaches of a small desert island, with a cluster of palms at the centre, a stone tower to the north and a large outcropping of rock to the south. East is the open sea, and further the white cliffs that mark the beginning of dry land; north and south you can row round the island.                                                                                                                                                                                                             You are drifting in calm, shallow and sunlit waters not far from the southern beaches of a desert island. The sun's warmth makes you relaxed and dreamy; you feel you don't want to row any more, that you will just let the ocean carry you off to distant lands.... Of course, this is a ridiculous idea.                                                                                                                                                                                                                     All around is water, though to the north and further south you can see the shores of islands, and some way to the east is the mainland itself.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  You are sailing over a vast expanse of gleaming and sunlit sea, close to two islands to the north and south, but some way away from the mainland to the east. Further west the ocean continues as far as the eye can see, unpunctuated by islands until the western horizon.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    You are sailing into the vast and uncharted western ocean; facing east, you can see small islands and - much further - the white cliffs of the mainland, all gradually receding as you head into the West.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      You are rowing slowly and steadily into the emptiness of the seas to the far south of the Realm. But though you try your hardest, you can't help feeling that you're not getting anywhere. Volcano Island is still firmly to your west, and a strange bank of thick fog to the northeast; while the blue waters of the more northerly seas do not seem to be receding at all...                                                                                                                                                 You are sailing the far western seas, west of Skull Island (named for the building on its top shaped like an evil skull facing east) and north of Volcano Island - the reason for this name being obvious when you see the plume of smoke that rises from its peak. Some distance to the north you can see a third island. West there is no land and the sea stretches on unbroken to the horizon.                                                                                                                              You are off the northwestern shores of Skull Island, a bleak, barren and stony place with no vegetation whose only interesting feature is the skull-shaped edifice on its peak (the island slopes steeply upwards from the sea). You may land here if you choose; round the island to the south the rocks are too steep to get onto land.                                                                                                                                                                                       You are close to the northeast shores of Skull Island and may land here if you choose; round the island to the south the rocks are too steep to climb, but here the stony peak slopes down to the waterline and the rocks - though still steep - are negotiable. You could also row round the island to the west or head out into the sea in other directions. To the east you can just make out the mainland and the harbour of the great city.                                                                                You are southeast of the steep cliffs which drop almost vertically from the peak of Skull Island all along its south shores, making access to the skull-shaped building on its top impossible from the south side. You could of course row north or west round the island in search of a better landing area, or head southwards towards an even taller island, almost a mountain, rising out of the water in this direction; from whose peak there trails a faint plume of smoke.                                              This area of the sea is close to the tall cliffs which block off access to Skull Island's southern side - though landing on the island is possible by going round it to the north or the east. You are also very close to a second island - this is the point where Skull Island and Volcano island come very close together, and its shores are to the southwest. If you don't fancy that the seas continue in any other direction....                                                                                         You are passing through the game's far western seas, close to both Skull Island (some way to the west) and Volcano Island to the south and southwest. Further west the seas are empty and stretch on to the furthest horizon.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   You are between the shores of Volcano Island (to the south and west) and Skull Island to the north - though looking in that direction it seems as though you wouldn't be able to land there from the south, because of the high cliffs on that side of the island. East-north-easterly is the mainland, some distance away across the water.                                                                                                                                                                                    You are in shallow waters north of the lowest slopes of the volcano, rising out of the sea to your south. It should be possible to land and climb it. You can sail round the mountain to the west and southeast; heading west or north will take you away from it.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              You're in the sea on the eastern side of the volcano, where the mountainside is at its least steep and it should be possible to climb the slopes. You might land there, head round the volcano to the north or southwest, or head off into the eastern sea; the way south and southeast is blocked by lava thrown off by the volcano, creating a treacherous area of jagged rocks which it would be folly to try to navigate.                                                                                                   You have rowed round to the southeast side of the volcano, and can look up its steep slopes to the lip of the fuming crater at the top. You could probably land here, as the slopes to the northwest are comparatively shallow; or you could row round the volcano to the north or west. All ways south and east are blocked by lava which, thrown out by countless eruptions over the years, has formed a barrier of jagged and dangerous rocks which are completely un-navigable.                                             This is the sea southwest of the volcano. It also seems as if this is the furthest southwest you can come, for all around to the south, west and southwest is a ring of solidified lava - jagged and dangerous rocks - which block completely any rowing in that direction. Neither can you ascend the slopes of the volcano; they are too steep here, falling in great crags and chasms almost vertically from the peak. So you must go round the mountain either to north or west.                                            You are in the sea off the northwestern side of the volcano. You cannot land on it here, as the slopes to the southeast are much too steep; nor can you go north or west, because the lava thrown off by the volcano forms a jagged and dangerous barrier of stone in those directions. But you can row round the mountain to the east and south, or head away from it to the northeast.                                                                                                                                        You have come to the centre of the palm grove and are standing beneath a large and tall palm. At first you are only interested in this tree for the shelter it gives from the burning sun; but as you rest beneath it you notice strange signs and runes carved deep into the bark. You wonder if something might have been hidden here....                                                                                                                                                                                     You're on the east side of a small grove of palms. Further east you can see the beach of this island.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           This is the north side of a little cluster of palms in the centre of a desert island. Further north you can see a beach and a somewhat incongruous tower (made from black stone) which rises from it.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           The west side of a palm grove, close to a large outcropping of rock which dominates the western side of the island and is climbable further west and southwest.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 You are on the south side of a palm grove in the centre of a small desert island. Looking southwards you can see the sea washing up a warm sandy beach.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         You are near the bottom of some steps which climb up the large rock outcropping which dominates the south-west side of the desert island. The steps, carved from the tough rock with obviously a great deal of effort, continue up the slope without wind or twist, and lead downwards to the sand.                                                                                                                                                                                                                             You are on a flight of steps carved from a natural rock outcrop which lead both up and down from here.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You're near the top of a flight of steps which were made to facilitate the climbing of this large rock outcropping, the dominant feature of the south side of this desert island. Further up is a ledge; below you can look down to the sand of the beach.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      You are on a narrow ledge in the rock at the top of a short flight of steps leading up a strange rocky outcrop on the southwest side of a desert island. The steps end here, and though the rock continues it is too steep to climb any further. However there is another exit from this location, in the form of a cave mouth - you can't tell from here whether the cave is natural or not - which allows you to go south into the rock itself.                                                                               This small cave is not natural, but man-made, and judging from the precautions the makers took to prevent anyone getting in, it was once used as a treasure store - perhaps by pirates. However little of the vast store of treasure that was once kept here now remains. There is just one exit, to the north.                                                                                                                                                                                                                 You are on the lower northwest slopes of Skull Island. South the steep rocks rise towards the peak, and east they continue at the same level. Those to the southwest look far too dangerous to climb; it looks as though a rockslide has carried away much of the mountainside. North, west and northeast is the sea.                                                                                                                                                                                                           The lower northeast slopes of Skull Island, scrambling among jagged rocks, close to the sea to the north, east and northwest. To the south a rockslide has made the rocks impassable in that direction; however you can walk round the island, west, or climb further up.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       You are standing on the northwest side of the peak of Skull Island, close to the temple - built in the shape of a skull - that gives it its name. The skull faces east, and you could walk round the rim in that direction to get to the entrance, or round to the west to get to the south side of the building. Or you could jump down from this flattened surface to the scree slopes of the island below.                                                                                                                   You are edging with extreme care round the south side of the Skull Temple. The southern half of Skull Island slid into the sea long ago, taking most of the path round the southern side with it, with the result that you are just inches away from a nauseating drop down to the sea and the rocks below. You had better move... you can go either east or west round the temple, with the eastern route taking you to the front of the temple and its entrance.                                                              These are the upper slopes of Skull Island, and the climbing here is hard going, as the slope is almost perpendicular and the rocks are a mass of small pebbles and scree which slip away from you as you try to rest your weight on them. Looking further up does not encourage you either, as you can see now clearly the great building, shaped like a skull, which is set on the summit of the island and gives it its name. It is not a cheery sight.                                                                      You are clutching a spur of rock which makes a good handhold to stop you sliding to your death, on the uppermost and steepest slopes of the northeastern side of Skull Island. You are quite close here to Skull Temple, the great building in the shape of a malevolent eastward-gazing skull that tops the peak of the island; a bit of climbing would bring you up in front of it and close to its entrance. Or you could head downwards towards the sea.                                                                    You are on a narrow shelf of rock on the top of Skull Island, which you can walk round to the north and south. You are also standing before a huge and hideous temple, built in the shape of a malevolent skull, whose entrance - between two of its teeth - is close by to the west. Looking up at the bleached white stone - a perfect representation of bone - and the glaring eye sockets, you are not at all sure whether you want to go in....                                                                            You are in the Skull Temple, a vast and eerie place whose main feature is a mighty throne (with steps leading up to it) set in the very centre of the hall.  Apart from this the place is empty. It is also uncomfortable, echoing, and very cold, and you feel no desire to stay here - and a positive desire to be gone....                                                                                                                                                                                                   You are sitting on the throne in the middle of Skull Temple. For a moment as you look around you can see this place as it must once have been; beautiful tapestries and cloth of gold deck the walls, brilliant lights shine from the roof and drive away the darkness, trumpets sound proudly from behind the throne and a crowd prostrate themselves in adulation on the rich carpeting before you. Then the vision fades, and you are looking at a bare and chilly hall once more. Steps lead down from the throne.          You're on the lowest southeast slopes of the volcano, close to the sea. You can ascend or walk round it to the north. The way west is too steep and too dangerous to attempt.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   This is the lowest northeastern slope of the volcano, close to the sea. You can walk round the mountain to the south or climb the steep slopes; to the west the rocks are steep and dangerous, and you would not be able to climb them.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         About halfway up the volcano, and it now becomes a struggle to avoid being burnt by rivers of semi-molten lava which wind their way sluggishly down the slope of the mountain. Further up the going is harder still, though below it is safer.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  You rest, fighting for breath, about halfway up the southeast slopes of the volcano. The heat here is far worse than it is down below, though not as bad as it is further up; and you need time to recover. Don't wait too long, though - the volcano may start erupting again any minute....                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   You are now close to the top of the volcano and the lava-filled crater, and are finding it difficult to avoid the slowly solidifying streams of lava - the volcano was erupting only a few minutes before, and this is only a brief respite...                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  You are near the top of the volcano and the rim of the crater. The heat from above is intense but bearable, though you still feel an urge to return downwards towards the sea. You realise with trepidation that if the volcano were to erupt you would be frazzled to a crisp in seconds....                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   You are on the very rim of the volcano crater, from which, a few moments ago, were spewing huge chunks of lava and molten rock and poisonous gases. The heat is still intense from the crater to the west, but the lava has receded, bubbling and spitting perhaps twenty feet down the shaft of the volcano. You could even venture westward into the crater.... or you could, of course, return extremely quickly down the volcano towards the sea and safety.                                                                You are about six feet below the rim of the volcano - but from the inside. You are in fact in the very crater of the volcano, and the heat is so intense that you imagine yourself to be burning away. You realise with a shudder that if the volcano were to start to erupt once more you would be - and you would, too, if you fell into the pool of molten rock not far below you. You can descend still further, or return upwards to the crater's edge.                                                                    You have come the closest to the pool of lava it is possible to come, and you have to cover your face to shield it from the heat blasting upwards from the bubbling, spitting, red-hot glowing pool of molten rock just ten feet below you - hotter than a furnace, hot enough to melt metal - certainly hot enough to frazzle flesh and bone to white-hot cinders, were you to lose your balance and fall... To the west and east, you notice with amazement, are two small tunnels; or you can return up towards safety.      This tunnel, obviously kept open by powerful magical forces (for otherwise it would long ago have been sealed up by the lava from the volcano to the west) leads eastwards into the rock and darkness.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          This east-west tunnel is lit dimly by a red and flickering glow from the west. To the east the darkness is complete.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            Your light flickers casting shadows round this small and clearly man-made cavern. At some time men must have decided that this was the perfect place to hide treasure; for who would think of looking in the mouth of an active volcano? Only an idiot like you, evidently.... The passage to the exit, protected from the lava by many spells, leads west from here towards the crater.                                                                                                                                        This narrow and low-ceilinged east-west tunnel connects to the wall of the volcano crater to the east. It is clearly protected by magical power, as otherwise it would have been blocked up long ago by the lava. Westward it leads into darkness.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              An east-west tunnel, lit from the east by a red flickering glow that is not daylight but the light coming from molten rock, leading into darkness to the west.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  This is a man-made, not a natural cavern; you can see that much in your dim light as you look around. The marks of pick and hammer are still on the roughly hewn walls, untouched by time or the lava. Powerful magic must have gone into the protection of this area from the force of the volcano; and much labour, too, in creating the tunnels and the cave. It seems a bit pointless, really, though you suppose that an active volcano is a reasonably good place to hide treasure....                                    You are in the great nonagonal entrance hall to Hamlet's Caves. In the southeastern wall - or the wall most nearly southeast - is the small stone door that gives entrance to the Caves. To the northwest and west are other doors, which are both wider and lower, so that you will have to duck under them. They have certainly not been made for humans to pass through...                                                                                                                                                   You are in a perfectly octagonal room, with four of the curious low, wide doors which characterise this part of the cave complex, to the west, north, east and northeast. However, the contents of the room are far more diverting than its exits... in the very centre is an octagonal well of white marble with stone steps leading down into it. In it swirls liquid - or possibly vapour - of many colours, which shift and billow in curious, transient patterns. It moves almost as if it were alive...                   You are in a bare cold cave, irregular but roughly heptagonal in its geometry. There are doorways west, northwest, southwest and southeast. Around the northwestern door a little dark water washes.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            You are in a hexagonal cave, elegant in the simplicity of its design... the finer points of its architecture are lost on you, however, as you are knee-deep in black, icy water and shivering uncontrollably. The mandatory wide, low doors are west, southwest and southeast.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  You are in the pentagonal cave, with doorways east, north, south and northeast, with dark water washing about the northeastern exit. There is a curious odour here and looking around, you see many tracks of some great beast leading in all directions, also scattered bones and human debris. Evidently this in the den of some creature of the caves, and involuntarily you find yourself glancing nervously about, anticipating its return.                                                                                You are in a small square stone room, with doors east, west and south. A little dark water laps about the eastern doorway.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      You are in a poky little triangular cave with low wide doorways south and east; east is a cave but to the south a low tunnel down which you will probably have to crawl.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        You are crawling down a long low north - south tunnel. The roof is cracked and fissured and in places you can see, high above, daylight and blue sky.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           You are in a circular cavern - not merely rounded, but mathematically perfect, the walls smooth as glass and polished as a mirror - and therefore as reflective; you wander for a while  before finding your bearings. When you are recovered, you see that there are small doorways both north and east, and a small hatch in the floor.                                                                                                                                                                                       You have come to the north end of a north - south tunnel. There is no way on from here; you must go back southwards.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            You are in the lower octagonal room. This is a damp dank cave with green slime oozing down the walls, and the stony floor lined with mosses and unpleasant fungal growths which give off a foul and putrid stench. There are caves north and west, a passage to the northeast, and to the south a tunnel which stretches on as far as the eye can see.                                                                                                                                                                          You are in the lower circular room. An iron ladder leads up to a hatch in the high ceiling of the cave. There is a doorway to your east, apart from that the cave is bare.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      You are in the lower pentagonal room. This was once used as a treasure chamber but it has long ago been looted by adventurers, and they have left little of use or value. The only door is to the south.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        You are in a narrow passage connecting two caves, one to the southwest and one to the northeast. Water drips from the ceiling, and stagnant water forms deep puddles on the floor. The walls of the tunnel are covered in a nasty green ooze, and the whole revolting place stinks like a sanctuary for alcoholic trolls.                                                                                                                                                                                                       You are in a nasty, dirty, smelly, wet cave, knee-deep in fungus-pulp and muddy water; every now and then this slimy mixture bubbles and ripples. Tunnels lead east and southwest; they look fairly awful too, really.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You are in a grotty damp little tunnel between two caves. Green slime oozes on the walls, and your feet sink deep into moss. A curious weed grows on the roof, hanging down like green hair.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    You are in a rough-hewn cave. A tunnel leads off to the west and above an aperture gapes in the ceiling, but the metal ladder has been broken off short and cast aside to rust - as it will quickly in these damp caves. Whoever lives in the rooms above obviously wants privacy, and someone must dwell there, for you can see above the red flicker of torchlight.                                                                                                                                                           You are in a long tunnel leading off southwards as far as the eye can see...                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    You are in a long tunnel leading off southwards as far as the eye can see...                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    You are in a long tunnel leading off southwards as far as the eye can see...                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    You are in a long tunnel leading off southwards as far as the eye can see...                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    You are in a long tunnel leading off southwards as far as the eye can see...                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    You are near the southern end of the long tunnel. South you can see a great arched doorway, and beyond, a hideous red light which casts monstrous shadows back into the northern darkness.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      You are at the bottom of a deep chasm, on the north bank of a river of molten rock, which flows from the west to the east and down into darkened caves. To your north is a steep, sheer cliff face; set in this is an arched doorway, beyond that a dark tunnel; and you cower back there from the heat. The narrow black shore between cliff and lava curves around cliff corners southeast and northwest.                                                                                                                     You are in a large empty cave. A tunnel leads west. There is a crevice in the ceiling, but it is much too high to reach.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        You are edging along the narrow black stony shore sloping northwest between the lava river and the cliff face. Here it bends west and east around cliff corners.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                You are on the narrow east - west shore of the lava river. It curves around the cliff northwest and to the east the shore continues beyond the mouth of the caves. You will need no light if you enter, for the caverns are illuminated by the red glow of the lava river as far east as you can see...                                                                                                                                                                                                                         You are in the entrance to the lava caves, upon the shore of the lava river itself. To the west is daylight, to the east only the dim red light of the lava river as it flows into darkness.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    You are in the lava caves, on the shore of the lava river. To the north is a narrow opening in the rock, east and west the shore continues.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     Here the shore comes to its eastern end, as the lava river narrows and diverges here, curving northwards across your path. You must turn back.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  You are on the broad western bank of the lava river, in a kind of tunnel including both river and shore. To your east a slender and flimsy bridge spans the flood, and passes into dark caves beyond. To the northwest a tunnel leads off into darkness and to the north this shore is cracked by many narrow chasms, though you might be able to cross. You could also head out of the caves, to the south.                                                                                                                    You are on the bridge across the lava river. West is the bank and east are dark caves. You look over the flimsy rail only for a brief moment, and then pull back in alarm at your danger. The whole bridge reeks of magic, necessary no doubt to keep the whole unsafe contraption from charring from the heat or melting like snow.                                                                                                                                                                                            You are in the Balrog's Cave, an unpleasant place filled with horrible red light from an unseen source. It flickers continually, and you jump back from every shadow. The floor is littered with the remains of those who came before you - scorched bones and charred flesh.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   Here the shore peters out against the northern cliff. You will have to return southeast.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        You are standing on cracked and broken land. North, the ground gapes wide across the shore, and you can only go back.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           You are in a narrow northwest - southeast tunnel. Another leads off north into darkness.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        You are at the north end of a narrow tunnel. You have come to a small stone doorway.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            You are at the northwest end of a narrow tunnel. You have come to a small stone doorway.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        You are in the West Chamber, a splendid natural cavern of great size and beauty, whose many stalactites and stalagmites, illuminated by your light, gleam in sparkling hues of orange, gold and brown as you wander entranced about the Cave. A narrow - man-made - tunnel leads off east and a stone doorway is to the south.                                                                                                                                                                                                  You are in a narrow tunnel connecting the East Chamber to the West Chamber, where a second tunnel, large and rounded, joins it from the northwest. It is clear that some great beast has made its lair here, probably to catch unwary travellers who pass through the junction...                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               You are in the East Chamber, a magnificent natural cavern of grand proportions. Here a tiny, ice - cold stream flows through the caves, presumably formed by melting snow from the mountains above. It enters via a small hole near the top and forms many clear pools in the rocks of the caves before flowing out of a tiny fissure. A narrow tunnel leads off west and there is a stone doorway to the south.                                                                                                                You are in a circular tunnel northwest - southeast between two caves. Another, similar tunnel branches off northeast.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           You are in a small grey cavern with a smelly, muddy floor which bubbles intermittently. In the very centre, a small and sulphurous geyser hisses and whistles.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  You are in a circular tunnel which goes southwest at one end and forks north and east at the other.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             You are in a small north - south circular tunnel which bends southwest at one end and continues north at the other.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             You are in a narrow circular east - west tunnel which bends southwest at one end and northeast at the other.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    You are in a circular tunnel which goes west at one end and forks north and east at the other.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  You are in a little north - south tunnel which bends southwest at one end and has a few steps down into a low dark cave at the other. From this direction you seem to hear the faint plashing of water.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         You are in a low cave half - filled with clear, pure water, with small fish darting about in it. It is numbingly cold. Southwards and out are stone steps leading up and out into dark tunnels, and some few inches above the water's surface is a ladder leading up into a crevice in the rock above.                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You are in a small cave; a metal ladder leads into a larger one below, where water washes. A small tunnel leads east to a T - junction.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         You are at a T - junction. Tunnels lead west, north and south.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  You are in the Gateway Cave. Two stone statues representing mythical figures flank a bronze gateway set in the north wall. The cave walls have been smoothed and ornamented, and the roof has been glazed and painted. The only other exit is south, down a small tunnel.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       You are in a small cave above a much larger one. You could drop down through a crevice in the floor, but as there is no ladder, you might not be able to climb back up.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         You are crossing the great underground lake, and have reached its centre, equidistant here from the western and eastern banks. Pausing briefly, you look about you and are awed by the splendid rock formations which rise in grotesque splendour from the water and the equally magnificent stalactites that hang from the high roof of the cavern - all illuminated in bright colours by your light and mirrored in the cool still waters of the lake.                                                                        These are the eastern waters of the underground lake: the water ends, abruptly, further east and northeast, at a rock shelf where you may land. The lake itself continues westward into the unfathomable dark. On the rocky bank nearest to you - to the east - a small stream has cut a groove, and this stream, splashing into the waters of the underground pool, would seem to be its source - though from this angle you are unable to tell where the stream itself comes from.                                            This is the northern part of the eastern bank of a great underground lake, whose waters, black and chill, stretch on to the west, punctuated only by the grotesque forms of stalagmites - reaching out of the pool to the rocky ceiling of the cavern, far above. The bank itself is bare rock, and continues to the south, whence you hear the sound of running water. East and north tunnels lead into the rock: the eastern tunnel is worn, as with many feet.                                                               You are now on the southern part of the east bank of the underground lake; and it is a gloomy and barren place, bare rock underfoot and dark cold still waters stretching west as far as eye can see or light show. A thin stream - bitter and chill - flows from a great crack in the roof and across the bank westwards to splash into the lake, the only break in the awesome silence. Eastwards a narrow and low tunnel has been delved into the rock; the bank continues north.                                            You are in a very low crawl, leading eastwards. This, it seems, is also the path of an underground stream; it flows about your hands and knees as you crawl and its bitter chill takes your breath away. Just here, though, it passes through a great crack in the floor to flow into what seems to be a very large and spacious chamber. You could descend, though you might not be able to get back up again, or you could continue east.                                                                                     You're negotiating a very low east-west crawl along the course of a chilly underground stream. At times the ceiling is so low that you must dip your face in the near - freezing water to continue. The stream divides here; one branch flows westward while a second passes down an even smaller crack to the north which you might just be able to squeeze into.                                                                                                                                                              You are passing along a narrow east-west crawl - extremely claustrophobic - which has been formed by the action of water upon rock - the water being the chilly underground stream that flows about your hands and knees as you crawl. The crawl continues westwards, in the same direction as the stream is flowing, while to the east you may enter a large room.                                                                                                                                                             This large and well-constructed room was clearly once part of the extensive mine workings that form the basis for these caverns; maybe even a control centre of some importance. The reason for its abandoned state is clear, though: a torrent of water pours from a large round hole in the roof, and the room is almost a foot deep in ice-cold water, which drains through a narrow crack in the western wall. The other exit is up though the hole, via a rusty metal ladder.                                              This is the lower part of a very rusty iron ladder in a smooth - walled rock shaft. The reason for the rust is apparent; a torrent of water falls from some source higher up the shaft, drenching you, and even making it difficult to retain your grip on the ladder, such is its force. The shaft continues above, while below the ladder leads into a wide chamber.                                                                                                                                                          You're on the upper part of a rusty metal ladder in a rock shaft. A torrent of water cascades down onto you as you cling to the ladder; the water's source cannot be seen, but if you were to go up you might find it, as you enter a large chamber in that direction. Downwards the shaft and the ladder continue.                                                                                                                                                                                                             Once you are able to look around you, you can see that this was once a chamber of some importance. The walls are lined with controls, all incomprehensible to you, and all now rusted and useless because of the stream of water which plays over them (and you!) from a crack in the ceiling - perhaps the Lake above has broken through the rock here? The only thing to have survived is a bell-rope hanging from the roof; the only exit down via a metal ladder.                                                           A narrow and low east-west tunnel in the rock. West it opens out into what seems to be a huge cavern, while east it goes deeper still.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You're walking down a very low tunnel - clearly not designed for humans - which runs east and west through the rock. East it ends at a low stone arch, and through this you can just about make out a small chamber or anteroom of some kind.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   This chamber looks as though it was once used for storing the many materials and treasures used and found in the Kobold mines. However, since the fall of the Kings and the destruction of much of the Realm the mine workings have gone downhill and much has been lost or abandoned. As a result this room now stands empty and bare. You can pass through low stone arches into narrow tunnels to north, west and east.                                                                                                      This is a low-ceilinged east-west tunnel, part of the Kobold mines. To the west it enters a small chamber of some kind, while to the east it seems to join other tunnels to form a junction.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    You're now at a junction, where a wide but low east-west tunnel joins another passage running southwards. The southern tunnel looks as though it ends at a door a few yards down, but you can't be sure...                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      You've come to the end of a tunnel from the west. This tunnel was clearly once intended to be a major part of the mine workings: it is wide and well constructed. But for some unknown reason the builders have stopped here; only the marks of pickaxe and shovel on the eastern rockface are left as testimony to their endeavour.                                                                                                                                                                                            You are in a short north-south passage, which joins others to form a T - junction to the north and ends at a stout wooden door, studded with metal, a few yards south of here. There is nothing remarkable about this passage, other than its surprising lack of height - you have to stoop to move along it, and you guess that it was not designed for humans to travel.                                                                                                                                                      This room is quite clearly a prison cell. It is barren and bare, with only a meagre pallet of straw lying on the cold flagstones of the floor, and the door - to the north - is of sturdy wood studded with metal. A grille, set perhaps twenty feet up - far too high for you to be able to reach it - allows some uninspiring daylight onto the scene. Not a very nice place at all, on the whole...                                                                                                                          A short and well-worn passage, north-south, joining a small chamber to the south with a much larger one to the north. There's nothing very interesting about this place.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        This is a wide and well-used tunnel, leading east and west. West it opens into somewhere much larger - it looks like quite a big cave, with a large body of water in it - and east it continues.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                You're in an east-west tunnel, wide and well used though with a very low ceiling which forces you to stoop. Eastward it enters a large and seemingly spacious cavern: you can't make out any details of it though. West the tunnel continues, and you think you hear the sound of running water in this direction.                                                                                                                                                                                                              This appears to be one of the few areas left in the caverns where mining still goes on. Rubble lines the walls on all sides (though you can pass through wide exits to south, west and east) and the marks of pickaxes are on the walls. Footprints - much too small to be human - are plainly visible in the dust, especially around the eastern exit. But there doesn't appear to be any work going on here at the moment - nor have the kobolds left any gems lying around...                                                This is a small passage, leading from the east to the west, and joining a very large chamber to the west to a much smaller one to the east. The floor of the tunnel is thick with stone dust, and in the dust footprints can clearly be seen.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   This is a storeroom, used for holding valuable treasures. In happier days this area would not have been open to vagabonds like you, but kept securely locked. However somebody - not long ago - has forced the great wooden door, which now hangs cracked and broken on its hinges. Gone are the luxurious furnishings which once adorned the chamber, and gone, too, are most of the treasures - gemstones and precious metals - it would once have contained...                                                               You're in a dark and narrow north-south passage, hewn from glittering black rock which reflects your light dimly from its smooth surfaces. This passage seems to have been made with greater care than many of the rude and roughly - hewn tunnels of the caves, and you wonder what might lie along it... To the south it enters a great natural cavern, and you hear the sound of water in this direction, but its northerly end is veiled in darkness.                                                                       You have entered an ancient and eerie chamber, hewn in its entirety from the glittering black rock of the caves. From the floor rises a stone column, smooth, and fifteen feet high - carved of the same stone as, and in one piece with the floor. Surmounting this is a grinning skull of the same stone, five times man size, facing westerly. North, south and east are high archways, leading into darkness.                                                                                                               This is an antechamber to the Skull Shrine through the western portal. A similar idol stands here, but of less size, and with many strange runes graven on its column. Before it, and occupying most of the room, is a great pit, circular in shape and sheer of side. Though you peer into the depths, its blackness is impenetrable. At the base of the pillar, you notice, a skeletal hand has been engraved, its bony finger pointing down; what this means, you cannot say.                                                You're in a north-south tunnel, narrow but high, and made entirely of a curious gleaming black stone, carved into many mysterious figures and runes on the wall. Further south the tunnel leads into a large chamber, but the darkness here is such that you can't tell what might lie within. Northwards the floor of the tunnel has fallen in, creating a chasm which is crossed by a makeshift and rickety wooden bridge.                                                                                                    You are on a makeshift bridge of wood crossing a chasm which has opened in the floor of a north-south passage. The bridge was not designed to take your weight, and creaks ominously as you cross it: below you can dimly see movement, and hear the rushing of water. You might - if you dared - drop down into the waters below, but would certainly not be able to get back up.                                                                                                                                              This is a north-south tunnel hewn from black stone. Northwards it joins other passages to form a junction, while south the floor has collapsed into what seems to be a sewer below - forming a chasm, crossed by an unsafe - looking wooden bridge; clearly the work of the Kobolds and not of the builders of these tunnels.                                                                                                                                                                                                   This is a 4-way junction, with passages leading north, south, east and west. In all directions the walls are of polished black stone and the tunnels lead into impenetrable blackness - except for the eastern one, from which you think you can see a faint glimmer of light.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  You're in a narrow dark north-south passage, which meets a junction southwards and leads into a largish chamber further north.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  This room is built in the shape of an octagon, mathematically flawless, hewn from black rock in the heart of a mountain. A passage leads south, but the feature which really catches your eye is an octagonal well in the centre of the room, filled with a vortex of colours which defy description and clearly magical. Steps lead down to it...                                                                                                                                                                              This is an east-west passage, made from dark rock intricately carved, joining a junction westwards and leading into a large room to the east. From this direction there shines a weird light...                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 You have entered a large room, with exits east and west. In its centre glows a pillar of light, reaching from the floor to the ceiling, made of  bright ribbons of colour, and these strange colours are writhing and changing as you watch, their sickly hues weaving a pattern that is both hideous and yet strangely attractive... You cannot tear your eyes away from the hypnotic shapes, and despite your efforts to master yourself you find yourself moving slowly towards the pillar...                                This small round chamber is completely bare, acting as an anteroom to the Room of Writhing Patterns to the west (through the only exit). You might find something here to act as a reward for having negotiated the cave: on the other hand, you might not...                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   This is an incredibly cramped north-south crawl, almost impossible to negotiate in places, and half-filled with freezing water, flowing swiftly north. Southwards this crawl joins another, still narrow and cramped but seeming much larger after the one you are in at the moment; northwards it continues.                                                                                                                                                                                                                   You're crawling along the path (leading north-south) of an underground stream, flowing northwards, which long ago forced a path between the rocks here and has since widened the crack to a point where you can just fit down it. Even so, it is difficult to pass along it, especially as the stream is ice-cold. Northwards the stream - and the crawl - join a wider tunnel of some kind; from this direction there comes a noxious smell.                                                                                   You are standing in cold, filthy and stinking water, up to your neck and flowing swiftly westwards. This east-west tunnel in fact appears to be the main sewer of the caves. Directly above you - but some twelve feet up - is a wooden bridge, crossing a great chasm in the ceiling of the tunnel where the floor of the tunnel above has collapsed. There is no way up to the bridge, though, and as the passage slopes down to the west the water would cover your head if you tried to go that way; so you must go east.   You are up to your chest in cold and filthy water, flowing quickly west through this wide east-west tunnel. Looking around at the many pipes which empty into the water - some dripping foul-smelling liquids - you realise with disgust that this must be the main sewer and waste outfall of the mines. You can't leave this tunnel here, though, except possibly through a great crack in the southern wall, from which cold but clean water runs into the main stream.                                                      You are waist-high in cold, filthy water which flows westwards through an east-west tunnel. The tunnel is sloping downwards to the west - which accounts for the swift running of the stream - and you surmise that going east would take you into shallower water.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             You're standing in a wide east-west tunnel, knee-high in foul and chilly water, which flows in through a grate in the eastern wall and can't be followed in that direction, and leaves westwards. There is also a bore-hole in the southern wall - you might be able to fit into it - and a deep crack has opened in the wall to the north.                                                                                                                                                                                     This is a very narrow north-south bore-hole, only negotiable by a flat crawl. From the south there wafts a foul smell, while to the north you can hear water running.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           You have entered the nest of a giant rat, stinking and filled with little other than bones, refuse and the filth of generations. A narrow bore-hole, leading north, is the only exit.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           You've squeezed into a narrow crack in the rock. You can go south into a sewer or try to get further north into the crack.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      This is an extremely tight place, wedged firmly between massive rocks to the east and west. You can retreat south - where the crack is marginally wider - or try to squeeze through the rocks to the north into a huge cave. From this direction you imagine you can hear a deep rumbling sound, something like a huge creature snoring...                                                                                                                                                                                      You are now in a great natural cavern, illuminated by your light in dancing shadows which flicker and chase one another across the gnarled and veined marble of the walls. From all around, echoing across the cavern, you hear a deep rumbling sound. You look around for its source...                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        You are in a small oblong room cut out of the living rock, which in less austere days was used as a cellar, but which now is almost empty. A short passage leads east. In one corner is a huge tun of wine, firmly fixed to the wall and supported on a hefty tripod. Although the tap on it looks to have rusted solid in the damp air, you might be able to fill a cup from it if you tried.                                                                                                                                  You are in a chill natural cave beneath Hamlet's Castle, on the north bank of a small pool. A short passage leads west into a smaller room. There is a wooden trapdoor in the ceiling, which you can just reach.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                You are in the ice pool between the north and south bank and between the east and west cave walls. Thin sheets and slivers of ice float silently around you on the ink black chill water and strange and slimy creatures stare from the quiet depths.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           You are on the southern shore of the ice pool, at the southern end of the vast cavern which contains it, on a narrow bar of land. There is no passage south from here, so you will have to re-cross the pool.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   You are in the northern part of the northeast tower base. High above is a narrow gantry, and high above that is some massive mechanical device. A high narrow window looks out over lands to the north.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         You are in the southern part of the northeast tower base. Above you is a narrow gantry, and still higher is a large, complex machine, full of cogs and gears and weights. The room in itself is uninteresting, with bare stone walls and a floor of hard earth; and it continues to the north.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  You are in a narrow east - west passage sloping downwards to the east. In the north wall is the postern gate, where the lord of the castle could escape in time of siege.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       You are in what you take to be the dining room by the wooden tables which run almost its whole length. It is a queer shape, like an obese L, and with poor light, for though there are windows in the east wall, they face only onto a shadowy enclave between the cliff and the northeast tower. There is a doorway to the south into the kitchens and another west into a small chamber.                                                                                                                                      You are on a fairly typical Elizabethan stage, with all standard fittings. At the back of the stage, to the east, is a narrow passage, presumably for the actors to make their exits and their entrances. To the south is an area intended to seat the audience.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                You are in the auditorium of a small theatre. To the south is a doorway to a small chamber; to the north you can climb down onto the stage.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     You are in a small chilly chamber north of the central courtyard, from which a cold wind blows. To the east is the dining room, and west is a more comfortably furnished room.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  You are in a pleasant chamber, with tapestry hung walls, and - luxury of luxuries - a carpet! Exits are north, east and west.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   You are in a large, well furnished chamber, perhaps used for entertaining guests. There are doorways south, east and west; north a narrow high window looks out over the land.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  You are in a curious little room, the result of the architectural oddities caused where the castle meets the cliff. Although north, west and eastern walls are ordinary enough, the southern wall is more of a southwestern wall and part of the living rock, the join between cliff and castle carefully mortared over. West is a door to the outside, east a doorway to a larger chamber than this.                                                                                                                           You are in a little outdoor enclave between the cliff and the castle, which is used as a graveyard, with high grass growing between the tombstones - and in one place a freshly dug grave. To the east is the main castle and north the entrance to a tower.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    You are at the bottom of a newly-dug grave - fortunately as yet tenantless. Though it is deep and the sides have been smoothed off with a spade, you could maybe scramble out at one of the corners.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            You are at the bottom of the northwest tower. Hamlet is obviously not too concerned about who shares his castle with him, for the tower has become a home to birds, and been allowed to crumble and erode. The stairs, certainly, are unclimbable beyond the first few steps, the walls are moss-grown, the window-bars rusty. The only exit is to the south, into the open air.                                                                                                                                                You are in a room more than half a natural cavern, a result of the castle's weird architecture. There are doors to north and east, and to the south is a bronze gateway flanked by two mythical figures. The walls are smoothed and ornamented, the ceiling glazed and painted.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 You are in the cobbled central courtyard, quite open to the elements. In the centre is a small sundial upon a column. There are doors in all four directions and looking up you see the four windows facing onto the courtyard; above, a patch of blue-grey sky.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                You are in the kitchens, warm and cheerful in spite of the doorway onto the cold courtyard to the west, as there is a roaring fire in the huge open fireplace in the east wall. East also is a doorway into a stairway room, and there are other doorways both north and south.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 You are in a stairway room, part castle, part cavern, where you can climb to the next floor of Hamlet's Castle. There is a doorway to the west.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 You are in a small homely room with a tiled, patterned floor. A cuckoo clock, now wound down, is fastened to the western wall. There are doors to north and south.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              You are in a large cavern, on the west bank of a shallow, fordable lake surrounded by weeds. There is a small doorway in the southwestern wall.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 You are nearly thigh-high in the middle of the lake, between the western and the eastern shore. The water is clear, and you can see in it brightly coloured weeds, waving slowly in the current.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                You are on the east shore of the weed-fronded lake, at the farthest east end of the cavern, where a little spring rises and feeds the lake. It is a quiet, pleasant place; and you guess that Hamlet had it constructed for reflection and relaxation - and also, more prosaically, as a source of water in time of siege.                                                                                                                                                                                                      You are in a well furnished chamber to the east of the entrance hall. North is another, larger room; to the northeast is a small doorway into a large cavern where the castle meets the rock.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   You are in a spacious yet sparse room with scanty furniture and no function that you can see. Exits are north to the open courtyard and south to the entrance hall of the castle.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               You are in the entrance hall to Hamlet's Castle, a well-furnished and spacious room. The gates are to the south, to the north and east are other chambers of about the same size.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               You are at the north end of a narrow metal gantry in the northeast tower, suspended perilously over the hard earth floor of the tower, far below. Above you is strange machinery - cogs, wheels, springs - and you surmise that, as the gantry leads no further north, it was constructed purely to allow the observation of this equipment. Unfortunately it means nothing to you. You must go south.                                                                                                                          You are at the south end of the gantry in the northeast tower. It has no rail, and you glance with a shudder at the hard earth floor far below. You have a good view of the machinery above - it looks like some kind of clockwork. There is a doorway in the southern wall and beyond that a passage.                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You are on a small observation platform in the northeast tower, from which you can watch the machinery. There is a doorway west, and a metal ladder leads up to a higher platform.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              You are in a long, broad north - south passage leading north into the northeast tower, onto a narrow gantry and south into a large room.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        You are on an observation platform at the top of the Clock Tower. East it continues to take you right over the machinery; and an iron ladder leads down.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        You are on an observation platform directly above the clockwork in the Clock Tower. The platform continues west, where there is a ladder to take you down.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      You are in a large bare cold room, which was once, you think, used as a storehouse - there are still hooks in the ceiling for hanging strings of onions, sides of bacon and so on. There are exits south and west to similar rooms, and in the northeast corner a passage leading north. A small doorway is to the east.                                                                                                                                                                                                        You are in Hamlet's Room, a place simply but comfortably furnished and well proportioned. Here Hamlet keeps watch over his cold northern lands and directs their affairs. There are two windows, one northerly overlooking the land, one southerly facing out over the cobbled courtyard with its sundial far below; and there are two doors, one west and one east.                                                                                                                                                            You are on the roof of Hamlet's Castle, looking over the battlements across the land below - you can see as far as Stilton Gorge. To your north you can look down on the central courtyard - with not so much as a rail to keep you from falling; to your west the cliff which forms the western wall of the castle rises yet higher, too steep to climb.                                                                                                                                                                       You are in a little room half built and half hewn out of the natural rock, with a little window in the east wall overlooking the courtyard below. There is one exit, to the north.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              You are in an old treasure storehouse, once full of beautiful things, now looted and despoiled. A window looks out over the graveyard - scarcely a pleasing view - and there are exits east and north.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You are in a room for storing items not in use: it has contained at one time or another tapestries, threadbare carpets, costumes, musical instruments, bric-a-brac and unsightly pictures, but now it is almost empty. Exits are south, east and west.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You are on a crumbling ledge of masonry in the southeast corner of the northwest tower. There is no way from this location in any direction except south.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       You are in a large room, bare yet warm, as it is above the kitchens and the chimney distends the eastern wall. There are exits north and south, and east to a stairway room.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    You are in a stairway room much like the one below it - small, square and with the eastern wall part of the east cliff. Stairs lead both up and down and there is a door in the western wall.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   You are in a well furnished bedchamber, with a high window in the southern wall facing onto the cold southern lands (a picturesque if not a very warming view) and its own wardrobe in the western wall. There is only one doorway, to the north.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               You are in a large mahogany wardrobe, smelling of mothballs and fur coats. East is its door, through which you can pass into a large bedchamber.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                You are at a four-way place between rooms. West is a passageway, north a small room, south a similar room over whose arched doorway has been carved the mysterious word 'PANDORA'.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              You are in the southeast corner of the roof of Hamlet's Castle, gazing over the battlements. It affords a good view of the coldlands - you can see the chasm, the ice hills, the cliffs - and dim in the distance Stilton Gorge. The eastern cliff - which is also the eastern wall of the castle - rises high above your head, too steep to climb. West and north the roof continues, northwest you can look out over the cobbled courtyard.                                                                                   You are in a small treasure storehouse in the hidden section of the castle. A window in the north wall overlooks the courtyard. The only door is to the south.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  This is a high, narrow room with whitewashed stone walls and a floor of cracked tiles, puddled with water. It has a single arched door, at one end of the room, and at the opposite end - the south - a window, narrow and barred. The overall effect is offputting; the place is dank and unpleasant, and stinks like a cellar that's been used since time immemorial as a burial-place for rats. Not to have entered would probably have been the healthiest option.                                                          You are in a brief passageway running east - west.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              You are in an oddly shaped cavern which has been incorporated into the main castle. It contains little of interest; the dust has lain undisturbed for years.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    You are on a little metal observation platform in the northeast tower, only a few feet west of the complex machinery which it houses. A ladder runs down to another observation platform and up to a higher, larger one.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        You are in the northeast corner of the castle roof. There are battlements to the north and east, northeast a tower (though you can find no way in) southwest you can look down onto the courtyard, and south and west the roof continues.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       You are on the northwest part of the castle roof. North you can look down over the land, west over the graveyard, northwest is a tower which you cannot enter from here, southeast you can look down over the courtyard (carefully; there is no rail) and east the roof continues.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              You are on the east part of the roof of Hamlet's Castle, above the stairway room. There is no view from here, only the cliff to the east (unless you count the view down onto the courtyard). North and south the roof continues.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               You're struggling through thick, shadowy forest close to the south of a great wall or cliff which blocks out most of the light coming from the north. Eastwards you can distinctly see some kind of building - old and ruined - through the trees, while south you can enter a small rounded glade, shadowed and overhung by the ancient trees.                                                                                                                                                                                 This is a pleasant sunlit tree-lined avenue, leading north and south. To the south it passes through a pair of mighty wrought-iron gates, once a strong barrier but now hanging crazily on broken hinges; to the north the road leads into a wide courtyard in front of a great palace of some kind, and you could slip through the trees to the east or the west (following a grassy path that leads off the main avenue in this direction).                                                                                   You're in part of the southern grounds of the palace that once housed the kings and lords of the Realm - long since deserted. The immaculate lawn that was once here has grown thick and shaggy, and grass and moss sprout between the cobblestones of the east-west path you stand on. The metal railings to your south - designed to keep the common people out - are rusted. Even the part of the palace directly to your north has ivy climbing among its crumbling bricks.                                                 This is the southwestern edge of the palace grounds; you're at a corner on a garden path - once pleasant and well-kept, now overgrown - that leads east towards an avenue, lined with poplars, and north towards a hill topped by a prospect tower. South is a high wrought iron fence, now rusty, but still serviceable; west you can see a tall stone tower, actually part of the city walls, with a partially ruined brick guardroom (of inferior workmanship) built onto it.                                                This is - or was - the main guardroom of the palace grounds, built as an extension to the older tower of the city walls to the west. Only the shell remains, though, blackened by fire and thrown down as if by mighty engines of war. The roof appears to have come down on the western side, completely blocking the door into the tower itself - you can just see the top of this door over a mound of rubble - so there is only one exit, east into the grounds.                                                            You're on a north-south path leading through an unkempt and dishevelled area of the palace grounds, once an ornamental lawn but now little better than a meadow. West is what used to be an artificial wood, which has undergone a similar fate; north the path climbs a little hill to a prospect tower; and directly to the east is a section of the palace wall, blocking your movement in this direction.                                                                                                                   This is a little clump of trees, once an artificial and carefully pruned copse but now much more wild and unconstrained. To the south is a partially ruined brick building and to the southwest a round tower adjoining it; neither can be entered from here. To the west is the city wall, and you wonder idly if this copse was originally planted to block off view of the unsightly buildings from the prospect tower you can see to the northeast. North the copse continues.                                              You are on the south slope of a gentle hill, topped by a prospect tower. A stepped path leads north-south up the hill here, making it easy to scale; or you can follow the path southwards, or go round the hill to east and west.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              You're standing at the top of a little hill, the centre of the western palace grounds, erected - you guess - to command a view of the grounds, long ago in the days when the City was great and its rulers powerful. You can go down in any direction (a stepped path leads south and down) or into a small prospect tower, built in mock-ancient style, from where you should be able to see most of the western grounds and perhaps even some of the City.                                                                    This is the western slope of an artificial hill topped by a prospect tower. You can go east and up, north or south round the hill, or west down it into a little copse by the western city walls.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               You're on the north slope of a small artificial hill which commands good views of the surrounding grounds - such as they are - and is topped by a prospect tower. You can go up the hill to the south, down it to the north towards a walled corner, or west or east round the hill.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            You're now on the eastern side of a little hill, not a natural feature but constructed by man (more specifically, a landscape gardener) to allow the lords and masters of the City to survey their domain. It is surmounted by a prospect tower, which you could probably enter if you got to the top of the hill; or you could go down towards a walled section of the grounds, or north or south round the hill.                                                                                                              You are in the palace grounds, standing by a herringbone red-brick wall to the east - part of the palace - and close to a little knoll to the west which is topped by a prospect tower. South your exit is blocked by a similar wall, but north the grounds continue.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           You're in a little copse - once an artificial wood, but looking much more natural after having been left to its own devices for years, perhaps centuries. The only immediate sign of man's hand is a wrought iron park bench, standing under the shade of a mighty cedar which must have been tall when the bench was placed here, however long ago. The copse continues southwards, while west is the stone of the great city walls, and east a gentle hill slopes upwards, crowned by some sort of tower.                     This is the furthest northwest you can come in the palace grounds; north is a crumbling red brick wall with an archway in it which you can pass through, while west is a much higher wall, cunningly built of indestructible stone. It is, in fact, the great wall of the city, which has stood for thousands of years and will doubtless stand for thousands more; craning your neck you can make out the ramparts and the walkway for the guards. South is a copse.                                                           This was once a walled garden, where the tender plants would grow away from the cold wind, sheltered on all side. The winds of time have blown through this place, though, and the plants are withered and dead, and the walls crumble in decay and ruin - a whole tower has fallen that was once part of the eastern wall, and destroyed much of the west wing of the palace in its fall, though the wall is still too high to climb. South is an archway and north an orchard.                                                You're in an area of the gardens walled in to east, west and north: still recognisably an orchard, though the trees have been untended many years and the gardeners would not recognise their neat rows in this tangled thicket. South the walled gardens continue, while east there's an archway in a partially damaged brick wall, which you might be able to get through.                                                                                                                                                    This is a corner of the palace grounds, close to the walls of the palace itself to the east and north. As you look at them you see that this ancient building was not unscathed in the disaster that overcame the city - the wall is cracked and crumbled, and looking up you can see that the whole of a tower that would have overshadowed you from the north has fallen leaving only a stump of brick. There's a knoll to the south you could climb, or southeast will take you round it.                                    You're in a courtyard, marble-paved, dominated by a huge fountain in the shape of a gryphon. Though choked with weed and long inoperable, it still retains some of its former glory and brings back echoes of long ago. North is the palace itself, seemingly untouched by time; its door stands open, though, and the golden gates themselves are long gone. West is a smaller yard, east are steps into the gardens and south a tree-lined avenue.                                                                            This small yard is an adjunct to the Court of the Fountain to the east, where the royal messengers and men-at-arms would tether their horses. The stable block - a low, tiled, red-brick building - surrounds you to south and west and can be entered to the south; there's a small door into the main palace to the north. From the west, distantly, you seem to hear the ringing of a hammer on metal.                                                                                                                       This is the stables, where all the horses of the household were fed and watered. Nothing of that remains; the room is completely bare. An exit leads onto the stable yard northwards, and a smaller door leads west.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            You're in the ostler's room, a small unfurnished chamber where the stablemen would sleep when the day was over, with a single window high in the western wall. Doors lead north and east; from the northern door comes the sound of someone or something hammering on metal.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    You have entered the smithy, where the horses were shod. All around are examples of the smith's art and tools of his trade - most of them far too heavy for a weakling like you to lift. Despite the daylight streaming in from windows to the east and west, the smithy is lit up by the red glow of a forge set in the north wall - presumably operated by magic, as there are no bellows that you can see. An arched doorway leads southwards, the only exit.                                                                You have entered the formal gardens of the palace and are on an east-west gravelled path leading west into a courtyard (up a little flight of steps) and east into the centre of the gardens. Unlike the western section of the grounds, these gardens are largely intact and the flowers still bloom in their stylised, ornate patterns as though somebody has been tending them.                                                                                                                                              This is the centre of the palace's formal gardens, a small gravelled square where paths from north, west, east and south meet. In the centre of the square stands a pedestal, once, you guess, the support for a statue or fountain, now vanished: this is the only sign of the damage done in the fall of the city, though, and the gardens themselves are as well-tended as they must ever have been.                                                                                                                         You're walking down a gravelled north-south path in the formal gardens of the palace, a pleasant area untouched by the devastation that has overtaken much of the rest of the City. South is the centre of the gardens and northwards you can see a summerhouse, close to the walls of the palace itself.                                                                                                                                                                                                                       You're on an east-west path in formal gardens which leads west to their centre and east joins a wide hedged avenue.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             A north-south path in the formal gardens leading north to the centre of this area and south through a garden gate into a field of long grass. Some distance to the north you can see a summerhouse, set on an immaculate lawn and close to the walls of the palace itself.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      You have entered a large field of unkempt grass, once a well-mown lawn but long since left to run wild. South is an iron fence, the southern boundary of the palace grounds: east a high thorn hedge blocking movement in that direction. You can go west, though, slipping between tall poplars onto the driveway of the palace, or north through a gate onto a gravelled path in a better-kept area than this.                                                                                                                This is a wide path surrounded to north and south by tall privet hedges  which block your movement in these directions. You can go west, however, where the path comes out into the open and enters the formal gardens of the palace, or east: in this direction the hedged avenue continues.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   You're at a corner on a wide garden path, surrounded north and east by tall hedges. South you can enter a hedge maze, while west will take you towards less enclosed areas.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     You are walking down a gravelled north-south path to the west of a well-mown lawn and to the east of the palace walls. South the path enters the palace formal gardens, while north you can get into a little summerhouse nestling in a corner between the walls to the west and those further north.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           This is an immaculate lawn, kept in pristine condition since the departure of the lords of the Realm either by dedicated gardeners or by powerful magic. In either case, the owners won't want you walking on it, so I should tread carefully if I were you... North are the walls of the palace, the windows looking down at you as you cross the lawn: south is the formal garden, fenced off to prevent you trampling the beds of delicate flowers, and east the lawn continues. West is a path.                             You're on a carefully mown area of the palace lawns, by the look of it a bowling green. The lawn continues to west and east, while north are the walls of the palace and south a high hedge which blocks your way.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              You've come to the eastern end of the palace lawns, which despite the desertion of the City long ago have remained undamaged and look much the same as they must once have done when they were trodden by the Kings of the Land. Here the lawn meets the city wall (to the east); your way south is also blocked, by a tall hedge, but you can go west across a bowling green or north through a small door in the palace wall.                                                                                                 This is a small storeroom, once the living quarters for the gardeners who tended the lawns and fountains of this area. Nothing much now remains. A door leads south into the gardens, the only exit: another door to the west has been bricked up and is completely impassable.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 You have entered a little summerhouse, whose windows look over the lawns to the south and east, the formal gardens further south, and beyond them the hedge maze. The summerhouse itself has clearly not been used for many years - its once bright and cheerful paint is now peeling and faded, the iron benches around the walls are corroded and decayed, and a thin layer of dust has settled over everything. The whole place has an aura of decay.                                                                        You are in the conservatory, once a place where exotic plants were stored and tended by the gardeners for the enjoyment of the lords of the Realm. However, it has long since been ruined: the west tower, which once stood south of you, has fallen, or been thrown down, leaving only a stump, and has destroyed most of the area around it. As a result there is only one exit, to the west: those to the south and east are buried under a mound of rubble.                                                                 This is the main entrance hall of the palace, built modestly in marble with gold fittings. An unobtrusive ten-foot wide carved oaken staircase leads up and east from here: to the south is the entrance itself, and you can pass through this into a sunlit courtyard. Other exits are north, through a lofty archway - from which direction you can also see sunlight - or west through a small wooden door.                                                                                                                  You've entered the guardroom, where the men-at-arms who guarded the palace would sit and quaff ale in their leisure hours. A sturdy wooden table stands in one corner, still stained with wine and beer, but nothing else remains. There are exits to north, south, west and east through studded wooden doors, the southern one leading out into daylight. Over the western door a sign reads "ARMOURY - NO UNAUTHORISED PERSONNEL." In the southeastern corner is a flight of steps, leading down.                            You are in the palace armoury, a place where the guards would store their deadly weapons when they weren't in use. Most of the weapon cupboards are, unfortunately, heavily padlocked, so that you can't get into them. A door leads east into the guardroom.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   This is a great oaken stairway, leading down into the marble hall and up to a landing. The treads have been polished by many feet, and are slippery, so take care!                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              You are on the landing, between a flight of broad oaken stairs to the west, leading down, and another to the north, leading up. Oak railings stop you going in other directions.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                This is a bright daylit passage, south of a great courtyard and separated from it by a stone colonnade. You can slip between two of the mighty pillars, or you can go east along the passage, west towards a small and unobtrusive door at the western end of the corridor, or south through a high archway into a marble hall.                                                                                                                                                                                                 You're in an east-west corridor, southeast of a bright courtyard (which you can enter by slipping between two of the high pillars which form a colonnade around it). North is a similar passage, to the east of the courtyard.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  A north-south passage, west of a courtyard and separated from it by a row of pillars that form a colonnade.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     This is an east-west passage north of a large bright courtyard, which you can enter by going between two of the high pillars which surround it. North a hefty bronze door stands ajar, and you can go through it.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               You are walking down a north-south passage east of a large open  courtyard, which you can enter by going west between the pillars which form a colonnade round it. East is a door, on which are engraved the words "OF THE TWO THAT ENTER HERE, ONLY ONE MUST LEAVE ALIVE."                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     This is an east-west corridor in the palace, close to a large window of leaded lights, to the south, through which you can see the lawn and - further south - the formal gardens.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               You have entered a large open courtyard in the centre of the palace. Paved with marble and surrounded by tall sandstone pillars that form a colonnade around it (you can pass between the pillars into the shade of passages behind them) it is a pleasant place. Looking up, you can see what must be the windows of the second storey - three of them, in the west, north and south walls.                                                                                                                                    This was the servants' quarters, inhabited by the lackeys, servitors, domestics, menials, drudges, scullions and scullery maids, turnspits, kitchen wenches, slaveys and other riff-raff that made up the staff of the palace. All are now gone, and the place is just a long, bare, stone - flagged room. Doors lead to the west, north, east and south.                                                                                                                                                                       You have entered what was the butler's room, set aside from the quarters of the other domestics to the east by reason of his higher status. He would hardly recognise it now, though, for in the fall of the City and the destruction of most of its buildings the West Tower - the stump of which can be seen to the west - fell onto the room above, causing the whole lot to collapse into this room. You can pick your way across the rubble to exits west and east.                                                        You're in the base of the West Tower - all that remains, for the rest fell some time ago destroying most of the west wing of the palace with it. It's not a safe place to stay. Steps lead down into darkness, or you can head east into another room: the exit that was north of here has been choked by rubble and the walls to the west and south, though damaged, are still serviceable.                                                                                                                                    This is the kitchens, once a busy and bustling place, now deserted and partially damaged - the western wall is crumbled and shafts of daylight gleam through the broken ceiling, while bricks and mortar lie scattered on the floor. The exit to the west has been choked by a fall of rubble and is impassable, but you can go east or south through studded wooden doors.                                                                                                                                                     You're at the western end of the Great Banqueting Hall. Chairs and benches lie overturned here, as if the inhabitants had only just fled the room, but dust lies thick over the benches and the great wooden table alike, spiders have spun their webs between the gaps, and rats have long ago carried off the food, while looters have taken the golden and silver plates and cups, so that in short this is a dismal place. Doors lead west and south.                                                                       This is the east end of the Banqueting Hall, and - like the western end - has an air of death and decay about it. The chairs and benches are strewn about in disarray and the great throne, once the property of the King, lies on its back, hewn with many axe-blows - presumably from adventurers trying to remove the gold leaf. No doors lead off from this end of the hall, though you can see a couple of exits in the western end of the room.                                                                           You have come to the eastern end of a long east-west corridor, lit by tall windows in the southern wall which look out over the gardens - providing a view which contrasts sharply with the bare uninteresting stone of the corridor itself. There was once a door to the east, but for some reason it has been roughly bricked up; so you can either go west, or north up a flight of dark narrow steps. A sign beside them says "STRICTLY NO ENTRY."                                                                          You're about halfway up a flight of steps, gloomy and dark. North is up, to a landing; south is down to a corridor.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             You've come to a small landing, at the top of two flights of narrow steps to the north and south of you. A door stands ajar to the west, and sunlight comes through the crack; but northwards the darkness is absolute.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         You're standing in a small shrine, the centrepiece of which is a tall pillar of some black stone surmounted by a carved skull, five times life-size. A door leads north, though you can't see what lies beyond it; south is a flight of steps leading up.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       This is a small circular room, with a pit in the floor where the rulers of the City would sacrifice treasures to their idol. A door leads south into a shrine.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  You're on a wide carved oak stairway, leading north and up to a passage and south and down to a landing.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        This is an east-west passage, carpeted and ornate, with a carved wooden door in the southern wall. A narrow window, to the north, looks down over a sunlit courtyard.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           You have entered the Grand Bedchamber, a sumptuous room where the most important and mighty in the Realm were privileged to sleep. Although the silken hangings and embroidered tapestries are long gone, the room still has a certain dignity of proportion and the four-poster bed against the eastern wall is a masterpiece of wood carving. Oaken doors lead west and north, and a great window in the southern wall overlooks the gardens and the Court of the Fountain.                                                   You have entered a wide, sandy-floored area, open to the elements, with a single door to the west. As you look more closely you see that mingled with the sand are little patches of blood, and here and there bones protrude from the dust. This is in fact the Arena, where condemned men and gladiators would fight to the death before the Lords of the City - you can see a gallery high in the eastern walls where they could stand and watch the sport.                                                                  This was the bathroom adjoining the Grand Bedchamber to the east. Though the fittings are all gone - looted long ago - the marble tiles and the sunken bath still remain, and your imagination can supply the rest - the heated water, the perfumed oils and unguents, the deferential servants, and so on. A frosted-glass window to the west stands ajar and you can look out over the gardens - and further west, across the city walls, you can see sunlight on the sea.                                                    This is a corner in an opulent carpeted passage, leading north one way and east another.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        You're in a wide and carpeted passage, leading east-west. The upper stories of the palace were the living quarters of the most powerful in the Realm, and are correspondingly luxurious, even extending to wide bay windows in the southern wall overlooking the formal gardens and the lawn. Directly to your south, though, is a wide oaken stairway which leads downwards to the ground floor.                                                                                                                               This is the east end of an east-west passage which extends the length of the first floor. An archway in the north wall leads into a small stone room.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           This is the base of the East Tower, and a metal ladder leads up through a trapdoor in the roof to what is presumably its top. (As this is the first floor, there must be a room below this one, but there's no way into it that you can see.) There are open doors to south and north; over the latter a sign reads "BE SURE TO SET PROPER COMBINATION BEFORE ENTERING." There is also a combination lock in the wall, but somebody's smashed it with a battleaxe...                                                            You are in a north-south tunnel which slopes down quite steeply to the north. To the south you can enter a small stone room.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    This is a steeply-sloping north-south tunnel, leading down to the north and up to the south. Northwards it enters a room, but the darkness inside is such that you can't see any details of it.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 You're in a curious little room in the shape of a right-angled triangle, with the hypotenuse being on the northeastern side and the southern wall being the shortest edge. As the room has no windows - it is in fact completely dark, except insofar as your light illuminates it - you can't see where you are in the palace or why the room is built like this.                                                                                                                                                              You are at a three-way junction where carpeted passages lead north, south and west. Westwards you can see daylight at the end of the tunnel. A door in the eastern wall is labelled "GUEST ROOM."                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               This east-west passage once led westwards to the West Tower. It does so no longer, for at its western end you can look through what was once a doorway down at the stump of the tower, which fell long ago. Although you can also get a good view of the walled gardens and the orchard from here, it is not a safe place to stand, as the brickwork which supports you is severely damaged. You can go east along the passage to a junction or north to a door.                                                                This was once a corner in a wide carpeted passage, leading east one way and south the other. Unfortunately most of the passage here appears to have slid down into the west end of the kitchens, fifteen feet below, and not only is it necessary to squeeze round the corner on a narrow ledge, but you must negotiate a two-foot wide chasm in the eastern passage right next to it.                                                                                                                                          You're in a carpeted east-west passage, near to a doorway to the north. The passage comes to an end further east and rounds a damaged corner to the west (damaged to the extent that you'll have to jump over a wide chasm in the floor and then edge round the corner on what remains of the carpet!) South is a narrow slit window which overlooks an open-air courtyard.                                                                                                                                                     You have arrived at the east end of an east-west passage and are standing by a large wooden door on the north side of the corridor. A brass plate on the door reads "The Right Honourable, Azarik Quimbar, Lord Chancellor. Do not disturb" but the door stands ajar and you guess that the Chancellor has long since joined his ancestors.                                                                                                                                                                                     A stairway alcove, with doors to north and south and a spiral stair leading up. The north door is carved with runes and occult symbols.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         This is the Court Magician's room, and as with most of the other rooms in the palace that would once have contained items of use to you, it is now completely empty of all the magical gear - it has been raided, not once, but many times. A door leads out to the south into a little alcove, and in the northeastern corner is a small door carved with a reasonable representation of the Giant Rat of Sumatra.                                                                                                             This eighteen-inch ledge is all that remains of the Chamberlain's room - the rest did not survive the natural disaster at the time of the fall of the city. In fact, the room below - which you can see clearly by leaning forward a little - appears to have caved in taking the floor of this room with it. A door leads south; as the other exits involve a fifteen-foot drop onto a mound of rubble, you'd better rule these out of consideration...                                                                        You have entered the Guest Room, an airy and spacious chamber set apart for those visitors who didn't merit the Grand Bedchamber at the front of the palace. Sadly, looters have stripped it down to the bare stone walls and floor, so there's nothing for you to pinch; but a window in the eastern wall affords a good view into a central courtyard below, while a mahogany door leads westwards.                                                                                                                           You are in the Chancellor's Room, a luxurious chamber befitting the one who controlled the Realm's finances in the days when the City was a trade centre for all Middle-earth. Although such trivia as solid platinum inkwells are long gone, there's still some extremely nice oak panelling on the walls (not removable...) Doors are to south and east - the eastern one's reinforced to deter thieves, though it looks like someone's tried to break it down.                                                               You have entered the Great Treasury - nice trick if you can do it - and are able to look around at the room where all the treasures of the Kingdom are stored. Mostly they're in great iron-bound chests, firmly locked and out of your reach, though there might be something knocking around that's worth getting. The only door (to the west) is a strong oaken one reinforced with strong metal bars. There's also a trapdoor in the ceiling, but it's much too high for you to reach.                                      This is the Changing Room, where the best laid plans of mice and men sometimes get a bit mixed up. The only exit is west, though if you're reading this, it probably means that you won't be able to get back...                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                You are in a secret room where a narrow flight of stairs leads up. The southern wall is oak panelling and there's a concealed door in this that you can go through if you want (it will probably not be visible on the other side, though).                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     This is the top of the East Tower. Emerging into the open air you look around - the view's certainly worth the climb. South you can see straight down to the lawn, then the formal garden, then the hedge maze and the driveway, and beyond those the City. North and west you can see over the palace, while east you can look over the City walls to the Realm. The only note of discord is the flagpole, broken two feet up, which you feel should be flying a proud flag.                                                   This is a landing on a spiral staircase which leads up and down from here. A door is to the north: a brass plate on it reads "LIBRARY."                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         You're in the western section of the library, a place where the most ancient and magical books of the Realm were collected by the lords of the City. The books are still here, locked away in cases of reinforced steel and magically toughened glass to keep off vandals and those who want to know too much. To the east the library continues, and a door leads south. In the northwestern corner is a large and ornate desk.                                                                                                You've entered the eastern section of a large library, the walls lined with bookshelves filled with imposing tomes, all securely locked away out of the reach of meddling hands. To your surprise, you notice that the shelves at the east end of the room are slightly out of line with the wall: in fact, they seem to form a door through which you could pass into darkness. Alternatively you can enter the west end of the library.                                                                                       You find yourself in a small dark north-south passage. The air is stale and cold. To the south the passage leads into a large room of some kind, you think, while north are some steps leading downwards. There's a rough wooden door in the western wall, without handle or keyhole, which you could push open and go through if you wanted.                                                                                                                                                                                   This dark unfurnished room was once, you guess, a hiding place for someone who needed concealment from his enemies. Probably untended even before the palace became deserted, it now smells of dust and decay. The only exit is an opening in the northeastern corner, leading north.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           You are on a narrow flight of steep stairs leading up and down from here. The steps are unlit and the treads narrow, and you have to concentrate to keep yourself from falling headlong.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        This is a stairway alcove. Spiral stairs lead down, and up to the tower top. There's a door to the north, with a golden crown of ornate design painted on its smooth surface.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   You have entered the Royal Bedroom, the place where the sovereign of the land used to sleep. Naturally then it was a luxurious place filled with valuables of every kind... equally obviously they have all long ago been pinched by thieving so&so's like your good self. The only exit is south, through a large wooden door.                                                                                                                                                                                                 This is the very top of the North Tower, the highest tower of the palace. From here you can look across the roofs at the other three towers - one of them ruined - and see the courtyards and a large sand-lined area which looks like a gladiatorial ampitheatre. In the centre of the tower is a large flagpole, reaching proudly to the sky. The only exit is down through a trapdoor onto a spiral staircase.                                                                                                               This is a dark earth-floored cellar below the remnants of the West Tower. Steps lead up while a gaping opening, like a lipless mouth, opens to the east. Above this ominous portal is carved in antique script the single word "LABYRINTH."                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     You have entered a dungeon, dark, bare and unfriendly. The iron door that used to bar the way out of this location (to the east) now stands ajar.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               You are in a bare cold chamber beneath the guardroom. Iron doors - once kept locked, but now open - lead west and east, and a ladder of the same metal leads up. Set in the floor, and somewhat incongruous, is a well of some shining black stone filled with a swirling vortex of glowing colours that lend their hues to the walls and ceiling of the chamber, giving it a magical aspect. Steps lead down to it.                                                                                                            This is the underground torture chamber where murderers, enemies of the state and those who criticised the cut of the King's beard were dealt with as befitted their crime. The instruments of torture - the rack, the thumbscrews, the shackles, the branding irons, the scourges and the cauldron to melt lead - are scattered around in disarray, while in one corner an Iron Maiden of Nuremburg stands open to reveal its deadly spikes. An iron door leads west.                                                          You're inside the Iron Maiden, hardly a pleasant place to stay with the bloodstained spikes digging into your back. It might be best to leave this place.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       This is the base of the Prospect Tower, set on a low hill to allow the best possible view over the landscaped gardens. The tower itself is bare, though benches are around the walls: the idea was that you could look out through the windows to west, northwest, southwest and south and wouldn't need a great deal of comfort. An iron staircase leads up to the open top of the tower, and a door leads out.                                                                                                                You've come to the top of the Prospect Tower, and can look around you at the gardens beneath. East and north the high palace walls overshadow the tower, while southeast you can see the roofs of the stable block; but the ornamental wood to the west and southwest, and the lawns to the south still retain some of their old form from this height, while northwest the walled gardens and the orchard seem warm and pleasant. Iron steps lead down to ground level.                                                        You're at a corner in a warm roofed passage northeast of a courtyard and separated from it by a colonnade. The passage leads west and south from here.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          You have entered the Royal Box, the room above the Arena where the nobility of the city could watch the spectacle of gladiators in combat with wild beasts or criminals. The western end of the room is a balcony, and from this you can look down at the sandy-floored amphitheatre below. A single door leads east.                                                                                                                                                                                                           This is a small narrow flight of stairs, leading up to the south and down to the north. Northwards the darkness is impenetrable.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                This is a corner in a warm roofed passage, northwest of a courtyard but separated from it by a colonnade. The passage leads east and south from here.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           You've come to a corner in one of the internal passages of the palace. The passage leads east and north, but there's a small door to the west which you could pass through, while to the northeast there is a large open courtyard, separated from the passage by a colonnade, which you can enter by passing between two of its pillars.                                                                                                                                                                                       This is the Minotaur's room, the centre of the labyrinth. The stone walls are carved with ancient patterns, some runic inscriptions now impossible to describe, others depicting gory rituals of blood sacrifice to the evil creature whose lair this is. Across the grey floor of the chamber are scattered many bones, the remains of the monster's victims, while in places the flagstones are darkened by dried blood.                                                                                                      You are at a junction in the labyrinth, a meeting of passages which all look horribly alike.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    