                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                You are in your boat on the forest pool. It is quiet and peaceful here, and you can lie back in your boat, looking up at the sky and the crowding trees, or down into the deep black waters where great fish swim lazily among the waterweeds. The north and south banks are too high for you to land, but you can row east or west; to the east great ancient willows throng the waterside.                                                                                                                                    You are in a pleasant wooded area to the south of the cliff. To the southwest are the ruins of the gatehouse and almonry, and southeast the abbey church tower still stands, tall among the surrounding trees. West, east and south are other woods similar to these.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           This is the domain of Nanjusi, God of Death and Destruction. Flames spring up around at random intervals, gushing like tongues of lava. High above you can see a column of rock leading up to an ornate throne, painted with real gold, while to the east is an ornately carved portal leading through into a darkened room. Moans and screams of mortal agony rack through your soul and echo mournfully around you. You realise that Doomsday cannot be far away.                                                             This room is dank and evil, with cold, dark bricks covering the walls which seem not to reflect light. Standing in the centre of the room is an ornately carved black marble desk, supporting a few black-bound books which you dare not touch. In the far corner stands a precious jade statue of a beautiful young woman whose eyes seem to sparkle and still contain life. The west wall holds a portal which is surrounded by the statues of various dragons.                                                               You are in a room that seems to throb with the red glow of lust. There are few ornaments here. However there is a glowing red throne pulsing in time with the throb. The throne is surrounded by a strange pentacle which fills you with such fear you cannot summon enough courage to go near it. There are no windows or doors apart from a huge pair of lips on one wall with the words "Kiss Me" underneath them.                                                                                                           This is the northeast corner of the downlands, just south and west of the abbey woods. To the south are some sickly-looking grasslands, while to the west the downs continue.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   You are in woods some way south of the abbey. This place is pleasant enough, but the trees seem somehow cramped and stunted, not as healthy as those to the north. To the south the trees are in a sorrier state still, entirely warped and withered, drooping by the banks of a foul lake. There are also woods similar to these to the east, while to the west the trees trail off into grasslands.                                                                                                                           You are among stunted trees some distance south of the abbey; to the west are similar woods. Northwards and eastwards the forest seems fresher and more alive, while further south the trees are withered and blackened, wilting sadly on the black shores of an unpleasant lake; they can scarcely be alive at all.                                                                                                                                                                                                            You are in an area of sick and withered grass to the south of downlands. To the west the land seems healthier, while to the east are the shores of an evil-looking lake, where the grass gives way to clumps of withered and stunted trees. To the south this dismal country continues.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         This is the northwestern shore of a pungent lake. This area was once green forest, but the foul water has poisoned the soil, and the trees, though still standing, are blackened, their limbs twisted and scorched, brittle and overgrown by putrid yellow-white fungi. To the north the woods are more healthy, while to the south, along the western shore, little grows at all. To the east the trees continue along the sad shore and to the west they give way to grasslands.                                              You stand among dead or dying trees, grown poorly in the poisoned soil, their wood black and charred and brittle and their bark flaking, their limbs twisted and their growth stunted. Loathsome yellow-white fungi grow and feed upon them. To the south a fuming lake slowly washes; in all other directions are more trees.                                                                                                                                                                                                  You are on the north shore of the bitter lake, among the stunted, withered, charred, brittle and fungus-laden trees of the area. West these trees continue; you cannot see what lies to the north or east, as all the land in those directions is hidden in a thick white swirling mist.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        You are in the south of an area of sick and withered grass. To the west the grasslands seem healthier, but to the east are the shores of an evil-looking lake, where little grows. The lands to the south are mostly bare of vegetation as well, being choked and poisoned by ash.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              You are on the western shore of an unpleasant and acrid lake. The soil here is poisoned and only a few spiky tufts of black grass grow, although further north you can see some clusters of stunted and withered trees. To the south these shores continue and to the west are scrubby grasslands.                                                                                                                                                                                                                              You are in ashlands, where light cinders have piled in dunes against the green knoll to your west. To the north are grasslands, but no grass grows here, only a few shrubs with sharp and over-bright blooms on thorny stems and broad sticky fly-trap leaves. To the south these ashlands continue, while to the east are the black soil shores of an evil-looking lake. To your southeast a black crag rises from the ash; it is too steep to climb.                                                                          You are on the black muddy western shore of a bitter lake. To the north these shores continue and to the west are ashlands. To the south a sheer black crag rises from the mud. It would be quite impossible to climb; even if it had been possible once, you can see that all the handholds have been chiselled away and smoothed down.                                                                                                                                                                                        You are in the northwest corner of the acid lake, to the south of the shore of the dying trees. From the surface of the water yellow- grey fumes rise slowly; they sting your skin, burn at the back of your throat and taste acid and metallic. East and south the lake continues.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             You are in the acid lake, near to the northern shore of stunted trees. The bitter yellow-grey fumes rising from the lake bite at your skin, sting your eyes and make you cough and choke. West and south the lake continues, but east is a high earthen bank which you can't climb.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             You are in the southwestern corner of the acid lake, to the north of a steep muddy cliff three yards or so high. To the west is the black and poisoned shore and north and east the lake continues. Thin wraiths of some yellow-grey gas drift up from the lake, making you cough, choke and sneeze. To the southeast, rising from the acid, is a tall sheer crag of black rock.                                                                                                                                                This is the very heart of the acid lake, where the fumes are strongest; you hardly dare open your eyes, but peering through half-closed lids you can make out that there is an earth bank, too high to climb, blocking the way to the south and west. Your best bet is not to hang around but to make for the northern or the western shore.                                                                                                                                                                                    These are dismal grey lands where ash and cinders have been blown up against the green knoll to the west. No grass grows here, only a few gaudy spiky blooms with prickly stems and broad sticky leaves for catching flies. North these lands continue, while to the west they give way to grey fens. To your east is a great sheer crag of black rock, completely unclimbable.                                                                                                                                                 You are clinging to the iron ladder fastened to the black cliff. Below you are the grasslands to the north of the lighthouse; above, the flattened top of the dark crag.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        You are on the flat top of the crag. You can see that there was once some great building here; it appears to have been destroyed - perhaps by fire - and now only a few heaps of blackened rubble remain. From this vantage point you can see north to the abbey, east and south as far as the mist, and west to the ruined watchtower and beyond. A metal ladder is fastened to the southern side of the crag, and seems to be the only way to descend.                                                                        This area has been used for the dumping of waste; although much tall concealing grass grows here, the ground and vegetation reek of some foul tar or oil - this whole area of grasslands would be reduced to ashes at the first spark. To the east the ground is heaped with slag hills, to the south are more grasslands, dotted with tree-stumps; to the north the ground has given way, leaving a steep drop down to an evil-looking lake. To your west a black crag rises, sheer, unclimbable and high.                     You are among grey hills of slag and dirt and waste from the time when the orc-lords joined in the struggle for power. To the north is a sheer drop into a foul lake; at some time or other the ground gave way, leaving a crumbling earth cliff. To the west and south are grasslands, those to the south dotted with tree-stumps. To the east are the black walls of a stern and ecclesiastical-looking building.                                                                                                             You are in the black chapel, a dismal and oppressively religious building; it has an aura of dark sins and their harsher penances. The high narrow windows are grimy and clouded and admit little light. There is only one door, to the south.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  You are in flat, featureless, dismal country; the northeastern fen. It is grey with scattered cinders from the ashlands to the north, and stinks of ash and damp. To your east are more pleasant grassy lands, to your northeast a black and unclimbable crag and to your southeast a clean white lighthouse. South and west the fens continue.                                                                                                                                                                                 You are in grasslands to the north of the lighthouse. To your north is a steep black crag; a tall iron ladder firmly bolted to the rock reaches from the firm grassy ground to the very summit of the cliff. To your west are some grey and rather depressing fens, while to your east the grasslands continue, dotted here and there with the stumps of trees.                                                                                                                                                                 You are in a green and grassy land dotted with tree-stumps; this might once have been a small wood, for the grass and stumps continue to the east. To your north and west there are also grasslands and to your south there is a slope up to the top of a cliff. Northwest is a sheer and unclimbable crag of black rock; to your southwest is a tall white lighthouse.                                                                                                                                                         You are in grasslands strewn with tree-stumps - the last remains of a wood - which continue to the west. South is a slope up to a cliff top and north some grey slaghills. To your east is the graveyard to a chapel. In the centre of these fields stands one tree not yet felled, an odd and slightly sinister looking thing, which you might be able to climb.                                                                                                                                                               You are high in the branches of an evil tree, a nasty black malformed thing with a stench of carrion and decay. Below you are more pleasant grasslands, dotted with tree stumps. Above you the tree's limbs become too slender and fragile to climb; you will have to go back down.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             You are in the graveyard of the black chapel. The site seems to have been ill-chosen, for the whole cemetery is awash so that in places you are forced to wade. The gravestones are crumbling and moss-grown and any writing on them cannot be deciphered. To the north you might enter the chapel, to the west are grasslands and tree-stumps and to your south there is a slope up to the top of a cliff. A thick white mist rolls in from the east. This place is distinctly depressing.                                     You are in grey fens west of a white lighthouse; as the door is on the southern side you cannot enter from here. North and west the fens continue and to the south is a swamp by the sea.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       You are on a pleasant grassy slope up to the top of a cliff, to the southeast. To the south or east you could walk around the slope, to the north are pleasant tree-stump-strewn grasslands and to your west your way is blocked by the white walls of a lighthouse.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            You are on the green and grassy side of a little hill, which slopes upwards to the south. West and east you can walk around the hill, and to your north are pleasant grassy lands dotted with tree-stumps.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      You are on a muddy slope southwestwards up to the top of a cliff. South and west you can walk around the side of the little hill, east you could go to an area of ash and mud, or north you could visit some sort of graveyard. To your northeast the land is covered by a thick white mist.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    This is an area of mud and soft grey dunes of ash. To your west are the lower slopes of a little hill, or you could go south - though the land there seems swampy and treacherous, perhaps it would be better not to trust your weight to it. You cannot see what might lie to the north or east; all that land is clothed in a thick white swirling mist.                                                                                                                                                                      You are in sinking mud, which is slowly sucking you down. To your north are lands of mud and ash, or to your west you might begin to climb the muddy slopes of a little hill. To the east the land is covered in mist and to the south is a mist-swathed slow and dismal sea, which you find frightening and unwelcoming in a way which you cannot understand.                                                                                                                                                                  You have come to the easternmost corner of the swamp, a dismal place scattered with ashes. To your north are grey fens, or to your east there are dunes of sand and cinders. To the south is a dull and listless sea shrouded with mist; you feel a strange desire to stay away. Northeast your way is blocked by the white walls of a lighthouse.                                                                                                                                                                              You are toiling through soft sticky dunes of grey ash, the shore to a sinister and misty sea to the south. To your north is the doorway to a white lighthouse; you might go in. West is the eastern edge of a swamp and east are the lower slopes of a little hill.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             You are on the western slope of a little hill. To your south the ground ends abruptly in a cliff; beneath are sharp rocks and the grey and misty sea. To your north you could walk around the side of the hill, or you could go down to the west, to an area of ash dunes. To the northwest your way is blocked by the white walls of a white lighthouse.                                                                                                                                                                       You are at the highest point of the little hill. To the south is a sheer drop. Below, you can see soft grey ash dunes and further south, the sea. North, west and east you can descend the hill.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                You are in soft grey ash dunes at the foot of a cliff too steep to climb, to the north. West, east and south you are surrounded by the grey and misty sea.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      You are on the eastern slope of a little hill. To your south the ground has given way and there is a steep fall; below, you can see cruel rocks in a misty sea. To your north you might walk around the slope of the hill, or you might go down to the east; this area, however, is one of sinking mud, and it might not be safe to trust your weight to it.                                                                                                                                                                    You are on grey and misty seas. It is impossible to see more than a few yards ahead of you in any direction, and you are out of sight of the shore. You cannot tell which is the best direction to row, but you feel a violent compulsion to leave these sinister waters.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       You are in the lowest room of the lighthouse, which has been decorated with dark runes and strange symbols. Drawn on the wall in red ink is a map of the Realm and the surrounding lands, written over with signs of power. There are no doors to this room, the only exit is up the iron ladder through the hole in the ceiling. Around this hole has been written the word 'ABRACADABRA' in large sea-blue letters.                                                                                                           You are in the entrance hall to the lighthouse, a clean bare whitewashed room with many windows high in the walls. An iron ladder leads down into a lower darkened room and a flight of spiral stairs leads upwards. Above the arch of the stairs are written the words 'SLEEPING BEAUTY' in bold black on the white stone.                                                                                                                                                                                                     You are on the spiral stairs in the lighthouse, between one room and the next. This place is dark and quite cold.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               This is the topmost room of the lighthouse, from which the light used to shine as a warning to ships. The lantern is gone but the strange coloured windows remain, so that the room is illuminated by a dim red light. Apart from a few long shards of broken glass beneath your feet the room is clean and bare. The only exit is down the spiral staircase.                                                                                                                                                                   This is the room where the Immortals meet and convene, talking of matters which are above Mortal understanding. Paintings of dragons in combat and of powerful mages adorn the walls, most notably a portrait of the first mortal granted the prestigious title of wizard, Bluewing. Against the wall lies a comfortable leather sofa, and a large round table is in the centre of the room.                                                                                                                                    You are holding on firmly to a rope ladder which leads up the side of a large galleon. Below you is the sea, coming closer and then moving away again in great swoops, which are both uncomfortable and unnerving, as a result of the rolling of the ship. Though the ladder here is some distance away from the galleon's side, it passes over the edge of the ship some way further up and looks more secure there. Or you could drop down into the sea.                                                                      You're on a sturdy rope ladder hanging over the side of a galleon. Here you are close to the overhanging edge of the ship and can touch the smooth wood of her side, but further down the rope dangles precariously above the sea. If you climbed a bit further you could get up to the rim of the boat.                                                                                                                                                                                                                        You're standing on the port edge of a large sailing ship, directly west of the main mast - the bows are pointing due north. The ship seems deserted: no flag is flying and no sail hoisted. You can't go south or north, as you are only kept in position here by holding onto the main mast's rigging, and you'd fall into the sea: but you can climb the rigging, go east onto the deck, or climb down a rope ladder that hangs over the ship's edge towards the water.                                                       This is the quarterdeck of a large sailing ship, and you're standing close to the large main mast. Although the ship is trim and clean, there is no sign of any crew, and you guess she's drifting, out of control. To the west it's possible to get onto the port edge of the galleon, where you could climb the rigging: or you could go north to the foredeck, south towards a cabin, or up a ladder to the south onto the poop deck.                                                                                        You're on the foredeck of a large galleon which seems to have been recently abandoned by its crew - without apparent reason. The prow points northwards, but the ship is making no headway and no sails are hoisted. Looking over the side you can see open gunports and rows of cannon, but no sign of life, and the hatches that would have allowed access to the main deck below are nailed and bolted securely. Your only exit is south to the quarterdeck.                                                                 This is the captain's cabin, entered by a door from the quarterdeck to the north. The room is bare and sparsely furnished, as befits a room that might have to be cleared for action at any time. Its main features are large barred windows looking out on the sea to the west, east and south.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                You are now on the poop deck of the galleon, the highest deck and the nearest to the stern. Like the rest of the boat it's clean and neat as if it had just been scrubbed: and like the rest of the boat, it seems to be completely deserted. The only sign of damage is a splintered hole in the planks of the deck that must once have supported the ship's wheel. The only exit is a ladder at the north end leading down to the quarterdeck.                                                                                You're about halfway up the rigging of a galleon. Above you is the crow's nest and further down the rigging meets the edge of the ship. You have to grip tightly as the boat rolls beneath you and the ropes twist in the wind.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 This is the crow's nest, close to the top of the main mast of a large sailing ship which you can see spread out below you. This is the place the lookout would have watched from, before the ship was abandoned, and once you've got used to the rolling of the boat you can see a long way from here - as far as the coast to the east. The sea is empty of other boats, as far as you can make out, and you may as well descend - by climbing down the rigging - to the deck.                                                 This imposing chamber is part of the headquarters of the Guild of Artisans, a powerful body whose task it is to regulate the use of skill and craft in the Realm. The only exit leads north through a high door. A notice on the granite wall reads "You may choose to be a wizard, a priest, or a ranger : speak your choice, or leave. Know that once made, your choice cannot be undone: and that your training will take up the rest of today, during which time you may not enter the Realm."                              This Guild was set up by Sunchild, an Immortal Assassin, who has been set among the Gods for his prowess at the Guild's deeds. The room is decorated with pictures of the great Realm killers - you recognise Axeman and Millicent - and examples of fine daggers and other weapons. In one corner stands the Guildmaster's throne: behind it is a picture of a halfling. Exits are through magical portals and lead to all areas of the Realm.                                                                                 This footpath travels down from the high western wooded glade and emerges into a small pathway which brightens as the forest becomes less dense and leads eastwards towards a small village. A tall thorn hedge runs parallel to the path on its northern side.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 You're on the crusty mud-caked road running from the village (which lies eastwards) towards a narrower western path. To the southwest the road joins a dirt track along which you notice the imprints of hooves and carriage wheels. In other directions the road is surrounded by a high thorn hedge (to the north) and a peculiar stationary mist.                                                                                                                                                                            This wide well-trodden road leads westwards, away from the village square not far to the east, into more open countryside along a wide dry roadway. To the north you see a timber structure from which you can smell a powerful odour of rawhide. The sides of wooden buildings block movement to the south.                                                                                                                                                                                                                    You stand in a spacious wooden enclosure which is well stocked with rolls of tanned leather, each of which is quite heavy and impossible to move single-handedly. A small window is visible at high level in the northern wall; the only door you can see is to the south.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      All around you there are products of the saddler's craft from the beautifully ornate riding seats to the harnesses which occupy most of the wall space. Most are far too bulky to be worth the taking. Behind a large heavy wooden counter you notice a door leading north, and to the south you may leave these premises.                                                                                                                                                                                                      As you enter this small ramshackle hut you are aware of a distinctly unpleasant smell. You guess that this is because of the dubious ingredients used in the adhesive with which the cobbler works. In any case, apart from a few rough sheets of leather thrown in the corner and some furnishings in the centre of the room, it is empty of items and the only exit is to the east.                                                                                                                                           You are travelling a straight road which leads south into the square of the village. As you look to the north, you see that progress that way is impossible -  a huge oak has fallen across the path. However a small hut stands to the west, its door invitingly open, and a glance in the opposite direction shows you a small path heading off behind the eastern buildings.                                                                                                                                                 This narrow yet well-worn pathway runs around the rear of a large timber framed building, from which you can detect the smell of hops and barley. You can go west onto the northern village road or follow the crescent-shaped pathway towards the south, where it meets with the road east of the square.                                                                                                                                                                                                                      You have entered the local village inn and immediately notice its sparse furnishings. However the sturdy looking timber stanchions and ceiling beams afford you a certain confidence in its structure. To the south you notice stairs leading to an upper floor; the large doors in the southwest corner open out to the village square. A cold draught blows through them, seemingly defeating the purpose of the roaring blaze in the large inglenook fireplace.                                                              As you enter this bedroom you stoop down somewhat to avoid hitting your head on the sloping rafters of the low roof. The window overlooks a narrow pathway but you find it too stiff to open. The furnishings are almost spartan, with a small cupboard standing against the wall and a dull mirror hanging over the minuscule bed. The only exit is the door to the south.                                                                                                                                                     This room appears fairly spacious - due to there being no furniture to speak of. It's obviously not been used in a long time, though the outline of a bed and table still remain on the dusty bare floorboards. Cobwebs hang from the closed window and you notice some thatch poking through the ceiling rafters where rainwater has penetrated. The only exit is the door to the south.                                                                                                                                       You are on the landing, at the top of a solid looking stairway (to the north) which leads down to the saloon and dining areas of the inn. To the northwest and northeast are two identical wooden doors leading to the bedchambers.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             This is the centre of the village, with timber buildings and huts around its perimeter. It's a pleasant, stone-paved area, no more squalid than you'd expect, but the whole place has an air of complete desertion, as though it had recently been abandoned.  To the northeast lies the village inn, and the blacksmith's is southwest of the square. Main roads lead off towards the cardinal compass points and, as you look towards the southeast, you notice a familiar wooden structure...                                This road leads out from the village square (which lies to the west) and continues east. To the north a narrow path leads behind a large building, but there's no way of getting into the buildings on either side of the road from here. Further east you see a large gate which seems to block the road.                                                                                                                                                                                                                      You are on the western side of a tollgate which is situated at the end of a track running west into a village. To the east you can make out misty areas of open fields, but the gate is firmly barred and there's no way through. A notice on the gate reads "PAY TOLL", although you can't see anyone to pay it to.                                                                                                                                                                                                            You are in the southeastern part of the square, the stone paving of which has been slightly raised to a platform to accommodate the heavy timbered stocks which stand here. They are extremely sturdy and no doubt afford the villagers hours of harmless amusement - traces of indescribably rotten vegetation still remain. To the east you see an open doorway, through which a pleasant smell of dough emanates, and you can re-enter the main square in nearly all other directions.                                       This small yet comfortable building houses the village bakery where you can detect the odour of fresh baked bread and cakes. The hot ovens are solidly built of stone and the blackened marks above them are proof of the ferocity of the fires. A large door leads towards the west; opposite a smaller opening allows you into a cobbled yard.                                                                                                                                                                                A single room is all that comprises the abode of the herbalist and local healer. Above you on ramshackle shelving several bottles of all shapes and sizes teeter precariously and as you look around the sparse walls you notice the insecurity of the entire structure. Sudden movements might not be a good idea, except westwards onto the comparative safety of the main road...                                                                                                                                            Several large potholes are evident in this wide mud-caked roadway which runs in a north-south direction. Smaller paths lead off to the west and east, and a very dilapidated looking hut stands slightly to the northeast.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      Timber frames at various stages of completion meet your eye as you enter this large building and an assortment of planks and wooden offcuts litters the floor. Above you, higher than a human can reach, is an open trapdoor leading into what you guess is a loft, but you can see no obvious means of access to that area. There are no other directions of progression from here, other than south to the market place.                                                                                                      You have entered a small, open-ended enclosure which is fronted by two large posts upon which have been securely stapled a pair of very large and heavy horseshoes. The anvil stands in the centre of this area and behind it against the wall there is a large black stone furnace. Although no fire burns here, the furnace is still warm as though it had recently been used.                                                                                                                                                Traces of carriage wheels and horses' hooves remain in this large area where, on selected days of the week, village traders and visiting merchants gather together to sell their wares to an unsuspecting public. Running northwards is a small pathway leading to a large building outside which you can see some newly-built timber framing: eastwards is a wide north-south road.                                                                                                                                            This long wide road which runs from the village in the north heads out towards a horizon which is indistinctly shadowed by a grey mist. Upwards to the east, you see a narrow winding road flanked by wooden posts and to the southeast you can enter a grassy field through a break in the fencing. A small path leads southwest to a turnstile set in a high wooden fence.                                                                                                                                                    You are standing in the middle of a vast network of farmlands which stretch to the far distant north and east. Unfortunately, deep troughs and artificial canals separate them and they would constitute quite a hazardous crossing, quite apart from the danger of being caught trespassing... A five-bar gate allows you southwards back onto the roadway.                                                                                                                                                                    This pebbled pathway leads up to a large white stone-built farmhouse, which gives you the impression of a wealthy owner. The doors and windows are bolted shut and you cannot find any means of access into the building, so you can only return south onto the farm road - other directions are fenced off.                                                                                                                                                                                                                    In between the high wooded post fencing which runs either side of this winding east-west road there are gated breaks - to both north and south - through which you can enter large open fields. The main village road is to the west and you can see a large stone building if you look to the northeast.                                                                                                                                                                                                                       This little dirt road (heading east-west) has been trodden down by the movement of cattle and you pick your way carefully to avoid staining your footwear. The end of the cattle tracks is at the entrance to a large cowshed, to your south, and opposite there is a small gravel path which leads up and around the farmhouse. To the east the way's blocked by high fencing, and you can't even see what might lie beyond.                                                                                                   These flatlands have been seeded recently, as the new growth of stubbled grass shows. You realise how boring grass looks when situated in such a vast expanse. You could sit here and watch it grow if you like... however should you wish to leave you can walk through the gate northwards onto an east-west road, or climb through the fence to the northwest onto a north-south one.                                                                                                                                        This dark and dank building has been separated into smaller compartments each of which has been filled to half capacity with straw and hay. The odour which assails your nostrils is fine if you like that sort of thing... As you look for a means of exit you see only one door, leading north onto a dirt track.                                                                                                                                                                                                             You follow the lines of the carriage wheels interspersed with the imprint of various animals along this narrow track running north-south; down from the road (to the north) into a wide open flat area. To the west is the edge of a forest, but eastwards rolls a thick bank of white mist, looking strangely sinister.                                                                                                                                                                                                        Around the perimeter of this large open space are the remains of a camp of Travellers and further signs of temporary accommodation can be seen to the southwest and southeast. Various scattered ash-filled remains of camp fires have been left and a sizeable garbage tip has been deposited in the centre. A dirt track leads across open countryside to the northeast, but to the west and east the land drops away into treacherous gullies filled with swirling white mist - you would be unwise to go that way.          Broken pieces of furniture are scattered around, further evidence for the former use of this flat grassland as a nomad encampment. To the west and south the land falls away sharply into valleys, shrouded in thick white mist, of which you can see little: the steep drop prevents you from going in those directions. The camp continues north and east of you.                                                                                                                                                             This is the southeast corner of what looks like a former Gypsy camp, bounded here by steep cliffs to the south and east: you can make out few details of the land below, as it's veiled in dense mist, but away to the south there might be some kind of tower. The remains of several horse-drawn caravans lie here and as you look over the south cliff you see far below you mounds of dropped refuse into which you'd rather not fall. The open area continues to the north and west.                                       You stand in a dirty cobble-paved yard which runs around the east and south sides of an untidy-looking shack. To the north a stone wall blocks off the alleyway, but you can see a small opening in the wall of a building to the northwest. A broad road can be seen to the west.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              This wide open area, surrounded by trees, is the start of a hard earthen path, worn by the feet of many travellers as they venture from the dense woods to the west towards the small village which can be seen in the near eastern distance. The vegetation to the north is too thick for you to pass through, but off to the west you think you can see some kind of building. To the south the woods are misty and ill-defined.                                                                                              This is the carpenter's loft, where he keeps (or kept) all the work which was too valuable to be left unguarded in the workshop below. A large room with a thatched ceiling, it's now almost completely empty - it looks as if most of the large stuff has been taken away. The only exit is a drop through a trapdoor to the workshop.                                                                                                                                                                                         These are gloomy, dark woods, filled with wisps of swirling white mist which completely obscures the area to the south. North and east of here the trees seem clearer, and to the northeast you think you can make out some kind of clearing in the forest. Westwards however the trees are stunted and distorted and the mist gives them an evil aspect.                                                                                                                                                                       These misty woods seem to be the eastern extremity of the forest. Further east you can see a rough track of some kind, leading more or less north-south, while to the northeast you can vaguely see another path going east-west. Directly to the south the mist, which is all around you, becomes so thick that you cannot see what lies beyond it at all. The forest continues to the north and west, though to the north there seems to be some sort of clearing.                                                            You stand under a small garishly painted canopy east of a turnstile in a high wooden fence. Set in the turnstile is a slot, next to which is a picture of a hand holding a small circular object. There is an iron door in the southern wall of the turnstile, discoloured by ferocious heat - someone has tried to fireball it off its hinges. Mist surrounds the area to north and east, but a small path leads northeast through the mist, up to a wide road.                                                                You're wandering aimlessly among bright circus stalls set out in a large field: the small booth that you have stopped to examine is one of the few that are open. A water filled trough runs along the front of the stall, just beyond your reach: above it a sign urges you to "WIN THE GOLDEN DUCK". You can move through the fair to the south or northwest: east is the exit, a turnstile set in a high wooden fence.                                                                                                       You stand in a cramped office, with no windows. The only light comes from a door to the north. The floor is covered with ash and soot, obviously the remains of the furnishings, but what surprises you most is the armoured nature of the door and walls. You realise that this must be where all the takings from the turnstile are kept.                                                                                                                                                                                     You've come to a stall covered with mirrors which distort your face into peculiar shapes. You spend some time pulling faces to amuse yourself, until you come across one really revolting reflection, which causes you to pull up in shock. You quickly realise that this mirror is completely normal! You may pass northwards between the stalls.                                                                                                                                                                              You stand before a huge steel wheel like structure, which is slowly turning, although you cannot discern what powers it; wooden seats are fixed to it at regular intervals. The area to your southwest is occupied by an enormous striped tent, while high wooden fences to the north and south bar movement in that direction. You may go southeastwards among the fairground stalls, or pass under the tent's guy-ropes, to the west.                                                                                         Standing before the tent, you marvel at the size of it. Large from a distance, close up it is HUGE! Over the entrance to the south is a sign, rendered in bright pastel shades. It reads "Welcome to Nightspawn's Big Top O' Fun". Regarding the demoniacal features of the face underneath, you are not surprised that the area is deserted. Paths run eastwards toward the fairground, and westwards, following the high wooden fence to the north.                                                                           You are standing on a sawdust covered area, surrounded by tiers of seating. To your east and west tall posts tower above you, supporting the huge tent. Immediately above your head is a rope net strung between the posts. It has obviously been abused, with large holes torn in it, as if great weights have been dropped through it. Below the holes the sawdust is strangely discoloured. The tent is dimly lit, but there is a patch of brightness to the north, through the tent exit.                                   Standing at the eastern end of the circus ring, you gaze into the dimly lit heights of the tent. High above, you can discern a small stage. A rope ladder leads up the side of the tent post, into the gloom, and to the west the ring widens to its centre.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    Taking a breather halfway up the eastern tent post you grab a chance to look round. Below you there is the circus ring, and above a small platform. You can also step onto a rope net, to your west, although it looks a little unsafe.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         You are standing in the centre of a worn safety net, obviously used to catch anything falling from above. It is very worn, and sags alarmingly. It might be a good idea to return east to the tent post, quickly.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               The small platform on which you stand is fixed to the east tent post. It has safety rails on three sides, and a ladder leads down through a trap in the floor. The tent roof is not far above your head, and you can make out all sorts of ropes and pulleys, used in the performances. The circus ring is considerably further away. A feature not apparent from below is the rope which stretches away to a similar platform to the west.                                                                                     You've reached a small platform at the top of the west tent post, high above the floor of the Big Top. This is where the tightrope artists would rest before the hazardous journey back east, and so the rope is the only way of leaving this area.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             You're standing next to a tall post which towers upwards to the roof of the tent. Near the top you can see a small platform, but you cannot see any means of reaching it. To the east of you the ring widens, and further east you can see another post. There is a small flap in the tent to the west.                                                                                                                                                                                                                         You are in a dark covered area, an extension to the circus tent, which contains a number of large and strong cages. All are completely empty of life. The smell in this area is quite overpowering. You may enter the main tent to the east, or go out into the fresh air westwards. This covered area continues past the cages, to the south.                                                                                                                                                                                  You have entered a storage area, where the circus props are kept when not in use. Amongst the various smaller items there is a large glass sided tank filled with water, with steps running up one side. The picture on one side depicts a man upside down in it, with his hands and legs manacled. A revolting smell drifts from the north, and the only exit is in this direction.                                                                                                                                            Standing on top of the large tank, you can see the water through a trap door in the tank top. It looks deep, and very cold. You may go in, or climb down off the tank, using the steps behind you.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              You are treading water in the top of a large tank. The water is freezing, and chills you to the bone. Above you is a trapdoor, and below you is, well more water really. The thick glass distorts the shapes of the items in the circus store, giving them peculiar appearances. If you can hold your breath for long enough, you may swim to the bottom of the tank.                                                                                                                                                           Taking small mouthfuls of air from the balloon, you manage to make it to the bottom of the tank. Your lungs feel as though they're bursting - you'd better head back to the surface soon.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       The camp fire in this clearing has been used recently - the ashes are still smouldering. This is where the circus retainers come after a hard day's performing, to have a barbecue and relax. You look at the unidentifiable lumps of meat in the fire, and wonder about the empty animal cages nearby. A path leaves northwards, bending round the huge tent which you may enter to the east. The clearing is surrounded by caravans: those to the south, west and northwest are open.                                         Entering the small caravan, you are confronted by a shelf of grinning masks. Below this is a mirror, and there are greasepaints and red noses on the table. The door's to the north.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            This is a roughly built, sparsely furnished caravan. At one end there's a board with a man-shaped drawing on it, covered in knife marks. Red-brown patches surround those knife marks within the shape. Eastwards you can enter a grassy clearing.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              This caravan is covered with arcane symbols, with silver stars and crescents much in evidence. In fact, it looks to you like the sort of place which would be used by a charlatan for parlour tricks, rather than a real practitioner of the arts. The door faces southeast.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    You are standing in the northwestern corner of the circus area. To your north and west further movement is blocked by the high encircling fence of wooden stakes that forms the circus boundary: close by to the southeast is the main tent of the circus, though you cannot enter it from here. Paths lead off to the east and south.                                                                                                                                                                                          You are in a large dimly lit room of which the main feature is a portrait of The Joker himself - he is grinning widely. The other walls are covered in bookcases. In one corner is a desk, littered with empty vials labelled "Nitrous Oxide - Industrial Strength". The strangest thing in here, however, cannot be seen. All you can hear are distant howls of maddening laughter - the sounds of the undead spirits The Joker has dispatched to another dimension. You feel yourself begin to giggle awkwardly...            